\p
\v 11 From TroasВҰ94919 weВҰ94920 sailed directly to SamothraceВҰ94922, andВҰ94925 then on to Neapolis the followingВҰ94927 dayВҰ94924.
\v 12 From thereВҰ94933 we continued on to PhilippiВҰ94937 whichВҰ94938 is a \add Roman\add* colonyВҰ94948 andВҰ94951 the capital city of the MacedoniaВҰ94946 districtВҰ94944 where we stayed for several days.
\v 13 On the Rest Days, we wentВҰ94966 \add down\add* to the riverВҰ94973 outsideВҰ94967 the \add city\add* gateВҰ94969 whereВҰ94974 we thought people might be praying, andВҰ94962 we spoke to the womenВҰ94989 who had met there.
\v 14 One of them was Lydia from ThyatiraВҰ94998 who was a sellerВҰ94995 of purple goods\f + \fr 16:14 \ft It's possible that Lydia dyed fabric and sold it, or that she actually made and sold the purple dye itself.\f* and although she already worshippedВҰ94999 \nd GodВҰ95002\nd*, the \nd masterВҰ95007\nd* openedВҰ95008 herВҰ95009 mindВҰ95010 and she readily accepted what PaulВҰ95016 was saying.
\v 15 So then Lydia and herВҰ95024 household were all \add ceremonially\add* immersedВҰ95019, and then she requested, вҖңIf you all consider me to be faithfulВҰ95030 to the \nd masterВҰ95033\nd*, comeВҰ95035 and stay at myВҰ95041 place.вҖқ So she persuaded us.
\s1 Paul and Silas get thrown into prison
\rem /s1 In Prison at Philippi; Paul and Silas in Prison
\p
\v 16 One time as we were walking to the prayerВҰ95054 meeting, we met a female slave who was possessed by a spiritВҰ95059 that enabled her to tell fortunesВҰ95076, andВҰ95049 thanks to that, to earn a lot of money for her mastersВҰ95072.
\v 17 She walked along behind us and shouted out, вҖңTheseВҰ95089 menВҰ95091 are slavesВҰ95092 of the highestВҰ95096 \nd godВҰ95094\nd* and they will be telling youВҰ95101 all how to be saved.вҖқ
\v 18 After she'd done this for several daysВҰ95110, PaulВҰ95115 was so frustrated that he turnedВҰ95117 around andВҰ95106 spoke to the spiritВҰ95119 \add in her\add*, вҖңI commandВҰ95123 you by the authority of \nd Yeshua\nd* the \nd messiahВҰ95129\nd* to leave her.вҖқ
\p
\v 19 ButВҰ95170 when herВҰ95152 mastersВҰ95151 realised that theirВҰ95162 profitable businessВҰ95161 was about to come to an end, theyВҰ95173 grabbed PaulВҰ95169 and SilasВҰ95172 and draggedВҰ95173 them to the authorities at the marketplaceВҰ95176.
\v 20 They broughtВҰ95181 them forwardВҰ95181 to face the magistrates andВҰ95180 saidВҰ95186, вҖңTheseВҰ95187 Jews are disturbingВҰ95190 \add the peace\add* in ourВҰ95192 cityВҰ95194
\v 21 andВҰ95197 teaching behaviour that we as Romans can neither acceptВҰ95207 nor practiceВҰ95211.вҖқ
\v 22 An \add angry\add* crowdВҰ95219 gathered around and the magistrates ordered for Paul and Silas to have theirВҰ95229 robesВҰ95231 torn off and thenВҰ95215 to be beaten with rods.
\v 23 They were severely beaten andВҰ95236 thenВҰ95236 thrownВҰ95240 into prison where the officer was commandedВҰ95243 to keep them secureВҰ95248.
\v 24 Because of that, he threw them into the innerВҰ95264 cell and locked theirВҰ95267 feetВҰ95268 in stocksВҰ95277.
\p
\v 25 Around midnightВҰ95282 PaulВҰ95287 and SilasВҰ95290 were prayingВҰ95291 and singingВҰ95292 praises to \nd GodВҰ95294\nd*, and the other prisonersВҰ95301 were listeningВҰ95295 to them.
\v 26 Suddenly there was a strong earthquakeВҰ95304 that shook even the foundationsВҰ95310 of the prison, and immediatelyВҰ95316 all the prison doorsВҰ95318 openedВҰ95313 up and the chains of all the prisoners came loose.
\v 27 The prison officer woke up, andВҰ95328 when he saw that all the prison doorsВҰ95336 were open, he drew his swordВҰ95343 to take his own life as he figured that all the prisoners must have escapedВҰ95349.
\v 28 But PaulВҰ95359 shouted out, вҖңDon't harm yourselfВҰ95363! We're all still here!вҖқ
\p
\v 29 The officer called for torches, thenВҰ95372 rushedВҰ95375 in and knelt down tremblingВҰ95377 in front of PaulВҰ95385 and SilasВҰ95388.
