\v 37 ButВҰ95581 PaulВҰ95564 responded, вҖңYou mean that after publiclyВҰ95571 beating us Roman menВҰ95573 without a trial, they threw us into prisonВҰ95580 and now they want to just quietly release us.вҖқ
\p
\v 38 SoВҰ95595 the officialsВҰ95600 reportedВҰ95593 this back to the magistrates, and they were quite afraidВҰ95614 when they heardВҰ95617 that Paul and Silas were Roman \add citizens\add*.
\v 39 SoВҰ95622 now they came to the prison in person, and appealedВҰ95631 to them, and escorting them out of prison themselves, asked them to please leave the cityВҰ95654.
\v 40 SoВҰ95665 after Paul and Silas left the prisonВҰ95669, they wentВҰ95671 to see LydiaВҰ95675 and after encouraging the believersВҰ95680 there, they left.
\c 17
\s1 Jason gets in trouble in Thessalonica
\rem /s1 Paul Preaches in Thessalonica; The Uproar in Thessalonica
\p
\v 1 After travellingВҰ95691 throughВҰ95691 AmphipolisВҰ95695 and ApolloniaВҰ95698, Paul and Silas wentВҰ95699 to ThessalonicaВҰ95706 whereВҰ95707 there was a JewishВҰ95710 meetingВҰ95710 hallВҰ95710.
\v 2 Paul's custom was to attend at the local meeting hall on the Rest Day, so he did that, andВҰ95715 for three weekends in a row he discussedВҰ95729 the scripturesВҰ95736 with them,
\v 3 showing them how that itВҰ95743 \add had been written\add* that the messiah would sufferВҰ95744 and be killed and come back to life, and then explaining, вҖңThis \nd Yeshua\nd* that I've been telling youВҰ95761 about is the messiah.вҖқ
\v 4 Some of them were persuadedВҰ95766 and joinedВҰ95768 with PaulВҰ95770 and SilasВҰ95773, along with a big group of godly GreeksВҰ95781 and quite a few prominent womenВҰ95786.
\p
\v 5 ButВҰ95800 some of the other Jews were envious \add of them\add*, and enlisted some of the troublemakers from the marketplacesВҰ95806 to form a mob. They stirred up all the people, and lookingВҰ95824 forВҰ95824 Paul and Silas so they could bringВҰ95827 them out, arrived at the houseВҰ95822 of a man named Jason.
\v 6 ButВҰ95834 when they realised that Paul and Silas weren't there, they draggedВҰ95836 Jason and some other believersВҰ95844 off to the cityВҰ95847 leaders, shoutingВҰ95848, вҖңThose two men who've gone around upsettingВҰ95856 the whole worldВҰ95855 have now come here as well
\v 7 and Jason has welcomedВҰ95863 them \add into his house\add*. They rebel against Caesar's decreesВҰ95870 and claim that \nd Yeshua\nd* is a rival kingВҰ95873.вҖқ
\v 8 They stirred up the crowdВҰ95885 andВҰ95887 the cityВҰ95891 leaders with theseВҰ95894 accusations,
\v 9 so the leaders collected a heavy fine from JasonВҰ95901 and the others, and thenВҰ95895 released them.
\s1 Many new believers in Berea
\rem /s1 Paul and Silas in Berea; Paul and Silas in Beroea
\p
\v 10 SoВҰ95908 the believersВҰ95909 immediatelyВҰ95910 sentВҰ95915 PaulВҰ95918 andВҰ95919 SilasВҰ95921 off during the nightВҰ95914 to go to Berea. In Berea they also attended at the JewishВҰ95929 meetingВҰ95929 hallВҰ95929
\v 11 and this group were more upper-class than the congregation in ThessalonicaВҰ95942. They eagerly accepted the messageВҰ95946 and examinedВҰ95953 the scripturesВҰ95955 everyВҰ95951 dayВҰ95952 to check if what was being taught matched what was written there.
\v 12 Because it did, many of the people believedВҰ95969 including quite a few of the prominentВҰ95981 Greeks.
\v 13 ButВҰ96023 when the Jews from ThessalonicaВҰ95997 found out that God's messageВҰ96009 was also being proclaimedВҰ96004 by PaulВҰ96007 thereВҰ96021 in BereaВҰ96003, theyВҰ96018 soon turned up to agitateВҰ96022 andВҰ96023 stir the crowdsВҰ96026.
\v 14 SoВҰ96030 the believersВҰ96038 immediatelyВҰ96029 sentВҰ96036 PaulВҰ96035 off to the coast, butВҰ96030 SilasВҰ96054 andВҰ96030 TimothyВҰ96057 both stayed.
\v 15 The ones guiding PaulВҰ96063 took him to AthensВҰ96067 before they headed back with his instructions for SilasВҰ96087 and TimothyВҰ96090 to comeВҰ96097 and join him again as soon as possible.
\s1 People of Athens like new ideas
\rem /s1 Paul in Athens; Paul Preaches in Athens
\p
\v 16 While PaulВҰ96110 stayed in AthensВҰ96104 waiting for them, he was upset in hisВҰ96114 spiritВҰ96113 as he observedВҰ96118 how idolatrousВҰ96119 the people were.
\v 17 SoВҰ96125 while he stayed busy having discussionsВҰ96123 with the Jews and other worshippersВҰ96133 from the meetingВҰ96128 hallВҰ96128, he also spent time everyВҰ96140 dayВҰ96141 with anyoneВҰ96124 who just happenedВҰ96144 to be around in the marketplaceВҰ96138.
\v 18 Some of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophersВҰ96153 enjoyed discussing things with him, butВҰ96170 others just mocked him, вҖңWhat does this babblerВҰ96165 want to talk about now?вҖқ
\p ButВҰ96150 others said, вҖңSeems that he's talkingВҰ96159 about strangeВҰ96171 demonsВҰ96172,вҖқ becauseВҰ96176 he was preachingВҰ96183 the goodВҰ96183 messageВҰ96183 about \nd Yeshua\nd* and coming back to life.
\v 19 So they grabbed him and broughtВҰ96199 him to the AriesВҰ96197 Hill \add where the council sat\add* and asked, вҖңAre we allowed to knowВҰ96205 what this new teachingВҰ96216 thatВҰ96210 you're bringing is about?
\v 20 It seems that youВҰ96221 have some surprisingВҰ96217 ideas for ourВҰ96228 earsВҰ96227, so weВҰ96229 want to hear what it's all about.вҖқ
\v 21 (EveryoneВҰ96249 in Athens andВҰ96242 even visitorsВҰ96244 often took the opportunityВҰ96251 either to explain or to listen to any new things.)
\p
\v 22 SoВҰ96261 PaulВҰ96263 stoodВҰ96260 up in the middle of the gathering on the hill andВҰ96261 spoke, вҖңMen of Athens, I've noticed how youВҰ96277 all are very religious,
\v 23 becauseВҰ96280 as I was looking around and observingВҰ96283 yourВҰ96287 objectsВҰ96286 of worship, I even discovered an altarВҰ96290 that was inscribedВҰ96295, вҖҳTo the unknownВҰ96296 \nd godВҰ96297\nd*.вҖҷ SoВҰ96300 without knowingВҰ96301 it, you already worship this \nd GodВҰ96297\nd* that I'm going to tell you about.
\v 24 This \nd GodВҰ96310\nd* who created the earth and everything in itВҰ96319 is \nd YahwehВҰ96326\nd* who's over heavenВҰ96321 and earth. He doesn't live in man-made templesВҰ96330
\v 25 nor can he be repaired by any humanВҰ96338 handsВҰ96337 and he doesn't need to be fed. \add On the contrary\add*, he's the one who gives lifeВҰ96352 and breathВҰ96354 and who gives us everything that we need.
\v 26 From one man he made everyВҰ96364 nationalityВҰ96365 that lives across all the earthВҰ96376 and designatedВҰ96377 their boundariesВҰ96384 and their futures.
\v 27 He made them so that they would try to discover \nd GodВҰ96393\nd*, and if they did search for him they might find him as he's not far from any one of us
\v 28 becauseВҰ96423
\q1 вҖҳWe live in him and are movedВҰ96426 by him and exist through him.вҖҷ
\m Even some of your own poetsВҰ96441 wrote,
\q1 вҖҳWe are all descendedВҰ96447 from just one.вҖҷ
\m
\v 29 SoВҰ96450 since we are God's offspring, we shouldn'tВҰ96454 be putting goldВҰ96458 or silverВҰ96462 or stoneВҰ96464 craftsmanshipВҰ96466 in the same class as the divineВҰ96472.
\v 30 In fact \nd GodВҰ96485\nd* overlookedВҰ96483 timesВҰ96478 of such ignoranceВҰ96480 in the past, but now he's informing everyoneВҰ96496 and requiring them to repentВҰ96497
\v 31 because he's set a date for when he's goingВҰ96505 to be fairly judgingВҰ96506 the worldВҰ96509. He's already appointed the judge who everyone can have faithВҰ96517 in because he broughtВҰ96518 him back to life from the deadВҰ96524.
\p
\v 32 WhenВҰ96526 they heardВҰ96525 about a deadВҰ96528 person coming back to life, some started mockingВҰ96531 butВҰ96526 othersВҰ96533 saidВҰ96534, вҖңWe'd like to hearВҰ96535 more about this from youВҰ96536 another time.вҖқ
\v 33 So PaulВҰ96545 leftВҰ96546 at that stage
\v 34 butВҰ96551 some people joinedВҰ96553 with himВҰ96555 and believedВҰ96556, including DionysiusВҰ96560 who was a council member, a womanВҰ96566 named DamarisВҰ96568, and othersВҰ96570 as well.
\c 18
\s1 Paul resides in Corinth for some time
\rem /s1 Paul in Corinth; Paul Meets Priscilla and Aquila in Corinth
\p
\v 1 AfterВҰ96575 this, Paul left AthensВҰ96584 and travelled to CorinthВҰ96587.
\v 2 There he came across a Jew named AquilaВҰ96593 who had been born in Pontus butВҰ96588 who had recentlyВҰ96597 moved from ItalyВҰ96602 along with hisВҰ96606 wifeВҰ96605 PriscillaВҰ96604 becauseВҰ96607 \add Emperor\add* ClaudiusВҰ96611 had ordered all Jews to leave RomeВҰ96620. SoВҰ96588 Paul approachedВҰ96627 them,
\v 3 and since they worked in the sameВҰ96635 tradeВҰ96635, he ended up staying with them and they worked together in their craftВҰ96650 of tent-making.
\v 4 On everyВҰ96662 Rest Day, Paul debated in the JewishВҰ96659 meetingВҰ96659 hallВҰ96659, and was persuadingВҰ96673 both Jews and GreeksВҰ96681.
\p
\v 5 However when SilasВҰ96692 andВҰ96693 TimothyВҰ96695 arrived from MacedoniaВҰ96688, PaulВҰ96701 was able to devote his full time to the messageВҰ96698вҖ”demonstrating to the Jews that \nd Yeshua\nd* is the \add promised\add* \nd messiahВҰ96707\nd*.
\v 6 ButВҰ96720 when they opposedВҰ96717 \add the message\add* and made false accusations, he \add publicly\add* brushed \add the dust\add* off his clothesВҰ96728\f + \fr 18:6 \ft In the culture, this was a demonstration that you're not responsible for their decision(s).\f* and saidВҰ96730, вҖңYourВҰ96735 future deaths are your own problem. I'm innocent \add of your guilt.\add* From now on, I'll goingВҰ96749 to the non-Jews.вҖқ
\v 7 SoВҰ96751 Paul left thereВҰ96756, and wentВҰ96757 to stay at the house of a man named Titos Justus who worshippedВҰ96769 \nd GodВҰ96771\nd* and whose house was next-door to the meetingВҰ96778 hallВҰ96778.
\v 8 KrispoВҰ96779 the meetingВҰ96783 hallВҰ96783 leaderВҰ96783 and all hisВҰ96795 householdВҰ96794 decided to follow the \nd masterВҰ96789\nd*, and many of the CorinthiansВҰ96799 believedВҰ96785 after they heard \add the message\add* and were immersedВҰ96803.
\p
\v 9 ThenВҰ96816 the \nd masterВҰ96818\nd* spoke to PaulВҰ96827 one nightВҰ96820 in a visionВҰ96822, вҖңDon't be afraid andВҰ96834 stay silentВҰ96836, butВҰ96832 keepВҰ96836 speakingВҰ96833 out
\v 10 because I am with you and no one can mistreatВҰ96848 you here because thereВҰ96852 are many of my peopleВҰ96851 in this cityВҰ96857.вҖқ
\v 11 So Paul stayed on for eighteen monthsВҰ96869, teachingВҰ96871 God's messageВҰ96876 to the people there.
\p
\v 12 Then at the time when GallioВҰ96879 was the proconsulВҰ96883 of AchaiaВҰ96886, the Jews united against PaulВҰ96898 andВҰ96900 brought a case to the tribunalВҰ96909 against himВҰ96905
\v 13 sayingВҰ96912, вҖңThis manВҰ96919 is going against the law by persuadingВҰ96918 peopleВҰ96921 to be worshippingВҰ96922 \add his\add* \nd GodВҰ96924\nd*.вҖқ
\p
\v 14 But as PaulВҰ96928 opened his mouthВҰ96931 to speak, GallioВҰ96934 saidВҰ96932 to the Jews, вҖңI would have accepted this charge if itВҰ96942 was a serious wrongВҰ96944 or evilВҰ96948 crimeВҰ96947 and would have listened to youВҰ96956 Jews.
\v 15 However, since it's a questionВҰ96961 aboutВҰ96964 a messageВҰ96965 and namesВҰ96967 and your own law, you all can see to it yourselvesВҰ96974 because I don'tВҰ96979 want to get involved in judging things like thatВҰ96970.вҖқ
\v 16 SoВҰ96983 he sent them away from the tribunalВҰ96989,
\v 17 butВҰ97004 theyВҰ97000 grabbed SosthenesВҰ96997, the leaderВҰ96999 from the meetingВҰ96999 hallВҰ96999, andВҰ96992 beat him up right there in front of the tribunalВҰ97003. ButВҰ96992 GallioВҰ97009 took action to stop them.
\s1 Paul returns to Syrian Antioch
\rem /s1 Paul's Return to Antioch; Paul Returns to Antioch of Syria; Priscilla, Aquila and Apollos
\p
\v 18 PaulВҰ97014 stayed on for quite a few daysВҰ97018 after that, thenВҰ97013 he farewelled the believersВҰ97021 and went to CenchreaВҰ97038 where he had his hair cut as was the custom for someone making a vow. ThenВҰ97013 taking PriscillaВҰ97031 and AquilaВҰ97033 with him, he sailed towards SyriaВҰ97027.
\v 19 WhenВҰ97048 they arrivedВҰ97045 at EphesusВҰ97050, he left the other two there while he went into the JewishВҰ97067 meetingВҰ97067 hallВҰ97067 andВҰ97048 had a discussionВҰ97070 with the Jews there.
\v 20 They asked him to remainВҰ97081 longer, butВҰ97075 heВҰ97085 turned them down
\v 21 although as he gave his farewells, he saidВҰ97091, вҖңI'll come back here again if \nd GodВҰ97110\nd* wills it,вҖқ then he sailed on from EphesusВҰ97118.
\p
\v 22 WhenВҰ97119 he landed at CaesareaВҰ97122, he wentВҰ97129 \add to Yerushalem\add* andВҰ97119 greetedВҰ97126 the assemblyВҰ97128 there before continuing on to AntiochВҰ97131.
\v 23 He stayed there for some timeВҰ97134 before travelling through the regionsВҰ97142 of GalatiaВҰ97141 andВҰ97143 Frygia strengtheningВҰ97147 \add the faith of\add* the believers \add through his teaching\add*.
\s1 Apollos teaches in Ephesus and Corinth
\rem /s1 Ministry of Apollos; Apollos Instructed at Ephesus; Apollos in Ephesus and Corinth
\p
\v 24 Meanwhile a Jewish manВҰ97162 named ApollosВҰ97155 (who had been born in \add the city of\add* AlexandriaВҰ97158) arrivedВҰ97164 in EphesusВҰ97166. He knew the \add Hebrew\add* scripturesВҰ97171 well
\v 25 and had been taughtВҰ97194 about the \nd master'sВҰ97184\nd* wayВҰ97181. Being a very enthusiastic person, he started teachingВҰ97194 about \nd Yeshua\nd*, even though he didn't know about beingВҰ97186 filled with the spiritВҰ97188.\x + \xo 18:25: \xt 2:1-4.\x*
\v 26 SoВҰ97207 Apollos started speakingВҰ97209 out boldlyВҰ97209 in the JewishВҰ97212 meetingВҰ97212 hallВҰ97212. PriscillaВҰ97218 and AquilaВҰ97221 listened to him, thenВҰ97207 asked to speak with him privately and explainedВҰ97229 God's wayВҰ97231 more accurately.
\v 27 Now Apollos wanted to go to AchaiaВҰ97274, so the believers encouragedВҰ97276 him andВҰ97255 sent a letter ahead of him to tell the believers there to welcomeВҰ97282 him, so when he arrivedВҰ97285 there, he was able to contributeВҰ97288 a lot to those who through God's graceВҰ97298 had also become believers.
\v 28 Apollos was \add also\add* able to thoroughlyВҰ97303 refuteВҰ97303 the arguments of the Jews and used the scripturesВҰ97310 to show that \nd Yeshua\nd* is the \nd messiahВҰ97313\nd*.
\c 19
\s1 Many filled with the spirit in Ephesus
\rem /s1 Paul's Third Missionary Journey; Paul in Ephesus
\p
\v 1 SoВҰ97320 thenВҰ97320 while ApollosВҰ97325 was at CorinthВҰ97329, PaulВҰ97330 travelled throughВҰ97348 the interior regions before arriving at EphesusВҰ97358. He found some followers there,
\v 2 andВҰ97377 asked them if they had receivedВҰ97374 the holy spirit when they had \add first\add* believedВҰ97375 \add in Yeshua\add*.
\p They replied, вҖңWe hadn't even heardВҰ97390 that there'sВҰ97389 a holy spirit.вҖқ
\p
\v 3 вҖңSoВҰ97405 thenВҰ97405 what were youВҰ97403 immersedВҰ97403 into?вҖқ asked Paul.
\p вҖңWith Yohan's immersionВҰ97411,вҖқ theyВҰ97404 answered.
\p
\v 4 ThenВҰ97413 PaulВҰ97415 said, вҖңYohan immersed peopleВҰ97422 \add in water\add* with an immersionВҰ97419 that went with repentanceВҰ97420 \add from their sins\add*, butВҰ97413 he told them to believe in the one who would follow him, that is to believe in \nd Yeshua\nd*.вҖқ
\p
\v 5 WhenВҰ97438 the followers heardВҰ97437 this, theyВҰ97440 were immersedВҰ97440 \add in water again, this time proclaiming their faith\add* in \nd YeshuaВҰ97446\nd* the \nd masterВҰ97445\nd*.
\v 6 ThenВҰ97452 PaulВҰ97458 placed his handsВҰ97460 on them \add and prayed\add* and the holy \nd spiritВҰ97465\nd* cameВҰ97463 \add down\add* onto them and they started speaking in other languagesВҰ97475 and speaking messages from God.
\v 7 There were aboutВҰ97483 twelveВҰ97484 menВҰ97482 in the group.
\rem /s1 Paul Ministers in Ephesus
\p
\v 8 SoВҰ97486 Paul started going to the JewishВҰ97491 meetingВҰ97491 hallВҰ97491 and for the next threeВҰ97498 monthsВҰ97497 he boldlyВҰ97495 discussedВҰ97499 and persuadedВҰ97501 them about God's kingdomВҰ97505.
\v 9 ButВҰ97515 as some of them refused to believe and became hardenedВҰ97514 against his teaching and started telling everyoneВҰ97535 that the \add Yeshua\add* wayВҰ97519 was evilВҰ97517, Paul stopped teaching in the meeting hall and taught the followers at Turannos' schoolВҰ97540 instead.
\v 10 This went on for twoВҰ97553 yearsВҰ97552 to the point that everyone in AsiaВҰ97564 \add Minor\add*, whether Jews or GreeksВҰ97579, heard the messageВҰ97570 about Yeshua.
\s1 The power of the master's message
\rem /s1 The Sons of Sceva
\p
\v 11 And \nd GodВҰ97589\nd* was doingВҰ97590 incredible miraclesВҰ97581 through PaulВҰ97594
\v 12 such that even if handkerchiefsВҰ97606 or apronsВҰ97609 that had touched hisВҰ97605 skin were placed on top of any person who was sick or troubled with demons, then they would recover and the evilВҰ97620 spiritsВҰ97618 would leave them.
\v 13 But some of the Jewish exorcistsВҰ97635 goingВҰ97632 aroundВҰ97632 attemptedВҰ97625 to use the nameВҰ97645 of Yeshua to drive out evilВҰ97643 spiritsВҰ97641 by telling them, вҖңI am imploringВҰ97652 youВҰ97653 all by Yeshua that PaulВҰ97660 preaches about.вҖқ
\v 14 Seven sonsВҰ97677 of the Jewish chiefВҰ97674 priestВҰ97674, ScevaВҰ97670 were doingВҰ97682 this.
\p
\v 15 ButВҰ97726 the evilВҰ97719 spiritВҰ97717 would answerВҰ97713 them saying, вҖңI know \nd Yeshua\nd* andВҰ97726 I recogniseВҰ97729 PaulВҰ97728, butВҰ97731 who are youВҰ97730?вҖқ
\p
\v 16 ThenВҰ97734 the manВҰ97742 who had the evilВҰ97751 spiritВҰ97749 would jump on them and beat them up so they'd end up escapingВҰ97766 out of the houseВҰ97770 nakedВҰ97763 and woundedВҰ97765.
\v 17 WhenВҰ97773 everyone in EphesusВҰ97784 heard about this, both Jews and GreeksВҰ97780 were frightened, and the nameВҰ97797 of \nd Yeshua\nd* the \nd masterВҰ97799\nd* was beingВҰ97795 honoured.
\v 18 Many of the people who believedВҰ97805 \add in Yeshua\add* came and confessedВҰ97808 \add theirВҰ97813 sins\add* and wrong practicesВҰ97812.
\v 19 Lots of the people who'd practicedВҰ97821 magicВҰ97820 broughtВҰ97822 theirВҰ97824 scrollsВҰ97825 andВҰ97815 burnt them in front of the others. WhenВҰ97815 the values of all of these were added up, it was \add huge\add*вҖ”worth around 50,000 silverВҰ97836 \add coins\add*.
\v 20 So that was how the \nd master'sВҰ97849\nd* messageВҰ97852 had a powerfulВҰ97841 effect andВҰ97854 won over many people.
\s1 The silversmiths start a ruckus in Ephesus
\rem /s1 The Riot in Ephesus
\p
\v 21 After all of this, PaulВҰ97865 decided in his \nd spiritВҰ97869\nd* that he would need to travel throughВҰ97870 MacedoniaВҰ97873 andВҰ97860 AchaiaВҰ97876 enroute to Yerushalem, saying, вҖңAfter I've been thereВҰ97888 a while, I will also need to go to RomeВҰ97892.вҖқ
\v 22 He sentВҰ97895 twoВҰ97900 of his workers, TimothyВҰ97907 andВҰ97896 Eratos, to MacedoniaВҰ97899 while he stayed on a bit longer in AsiaВҰ97918 \add Minor\add*.
\rem /s1 The Riot in Ephesus
\p
\v 23 ButВҰ97921 while he was still there, a major disturbanceВҰ97926 hit the Yeshua followers.
\v 24 A silversmithВҰ97937 named DemetriusВҰ97932 made \add littleВҰ97951\add* silverВҰ97941 shrines of ArtemisВҰ97943 and this businessВҰ97952 brought a tidy profit to the local craftsmenВҰ97948.
\v 25 Demetrius gathered all the workersВҰ97963 togetherВҰ97955 and told them, вҖңMen, youВҰ97971 all know that our prosperityВҰ97978 comes from this businessВҰ97976 of ours.
\v 26 ButВҰ97982 you've seen yourselves and heard from others that not only EphesusВҰ97993, butВҰ97982 almostВҰ97996 our entireВҰ97983 \add province of\add* AsiaВҰ97999 \add Minor\add* has becomeВҰ98019 persuadedВҰ98005 by this PaulВҰ98001 fellow, and now the crowdsВҰ98009 are sayingВҰ98010 that what we make are not \add real\add* godsВҰ98015.
\v 27 However it's not only us and our tradeВҰ98030 that is coming into disreputeВҰ98034, butВҰ98023 the templeВҰ98044 of the great goddessВҰ98041 Artemis is considered to be useless. This could result in a loss of power for the great Artemis that all of AsiaВҰ98066 \add Minor\add* and the inhabitedВҰ98069 worldВҰ98069 have been worshippingВҰ98070.вҖқ
\p
\v 28 WhenВҰ98073 the gathering heardВҰ98072 this, theyВҰ98083 became very angry andВҰ98075 yelled out, вҖңArtemisВҰ98087 of the Ephesians is great!вҖқ
\v 29 ThenВҰ98089 the \add whole\add* cityВҰ98094 was filledВҰ98090 with confusionВҰ98097 and the people rushedВҰ98099 to the theatreВҰ98105 and grabbed GaiusВҰ98108 and AristarchusВҰ98110 from MacedoniaВҰ98111вҖ”travellingВҰ98113 companionsВҰ98113 of Paul'sВҰ98115.
\v 30 Now PaulВҰ98117 wanted to go there and speak to the crowd, butВҰ98119 the believers wouldn't let himВҰ98129 go.
\v 31 Also some of the leaders from Asia \add Minor\add* who were friendlyВҰ98141 towards him, sentВҰ98142 messengers to him to imploreВҰ98145 him not to go to the theatreВҰ98152.
\v 32 Some of the people gathered there were yelling out something, butВҰ98166 overall it was just confusion, andВҰ98166 the majority of the people couldn't even tell you the reason why theyВҰ98174 were there.
\v 33 Some people in the crowdВҰ98178 selected AlexanderВҰ98182 the Jew andВҰ98176 sent him forwardВҰ98183 to speak, so he motioned with his handВҰ98195 ready to explain the situation to the people.
\v 34 But as soon as they recognisedВҰ98202 that he was a Jew, people started yelling, вҖңArtemisВҰ98222 of the Ephesians is great,вҖқ and this continued for over twoВҰ98217 hoursВҰ98216.
\p
\v 35 Eventually the cityВҰ98253 administrator was able to calm the crowdВҰ98234 and tell them, вҖңMen, fellow Ephesians, what person from around here doesn't know that it's Ephesus that's the templeВҰ98254 keeperВҰ98254 of the greatВҰ98259 ArtemisВҰ98261 and of this imageВҰ98264 that fell down from Zeus?
\v 36 Since all of this is unquestionableВҰ98265, itВҰ98271 makes sense for everyone to calm down andВҰ98275 not do anything recklessВҰ98277.
\v 37 These menВҰ98282 that youВҰ98279 presented here haven't stolen anything from the templeВҰ98287, nor have they slanderedВҰ98290 ourВҰ98294 goddessВҰ98292.
\v 38 So if DemetriusВҰ98299 and the silver craftsmenВҰ98307 with himВҰ98306 have a case against anyoneВҰ98311, they shouldВҰ98319 bring it to the courtsВҰ98314 and the proconsulsВҰ98317 and register the charges.
\v 39 But for the rest of you, if you have a grievance against othersВҰ98322, itВҰ98337 needs to be settledВҰ98337 in a lawfulВҰ98334 assemblyВҰ98336
\v 40 becauseВҰ98339 we're in dangerВҰ98340 of being charged with insurrectionВҰ98343 about what happened todayВҰ98346. And we would have no defence thatВҰ98352 we could respond with concerning this disorderlyВҰ98361 gatheringВҰ98361.вҖқ ThenВҰ98363 he told them all to go home.
\c 20
\s1 Paul travels to Macedonia and Achaia
\rem /s1 To Macedonia and Achaia; Through Macedonia and Greece; Paul Goes to Macedonia and Greece
\p
\v 1 After all the commotionВҰ98374 had died down, PaulВҰ98378 sentВҰ98375 for the believers, and afterВҰ98369 greetingВҰ98386 and encouraging them, he leftВҰ98388 \add Ephesus\add* to go to MacedoniaВҰ98393.\f + \fr 20:1 \ft As he'd already decidedвҖ”see 19:21.\f*
\v 2 As he travelled throughВҰ98394 the districtsВҰ98398, he challenged the people there with a lot of messages, until he eventually arrived in GreeceВҰ98410.
\v 3 He'd been there about threeВҰ98415 monthsВҰ98414 when he heard about a plot by some Jews to waylay him as he boarded a ship to return to SyriaВҰ98431, so instead he decided to return throughВҰ98442 MacedoniaВҰ98444
\v 4 with SopaterВҰ98456 son of PyrrhusВҰ98457 from Berea, AristarchusВҰ98461 and SecundusВҰ98463 from ThessalonicaВҰ98459, GaiusВҰ98465 from Derbe, TychicusВҰ98474 and TrophimusВҰ98476 from the province of AsiaВҰ98471 \add Minor\add*, and TimothyВҰ98469 all accompanyingВҰ98445 himВҰ98450.
\v 5 They went ahead andВҰ98478 waited for us\f + \fr 20:5 \ft Luke (the writer) includes himself here.\f* at TroasВҰ98485.
\v 6 SoВҰ98487 we sailedВҰ98488 out from PhilippiВҰ98495 after the \it Flat Bread Celebration\it*. We arrived and meet the others there at TroasВҰ98502 after a five-day trip, and thenВҰ98487 stayedВҰ98513 on there for sevenВҰ98515 days.
\s1 Paul's all-night discussions in Troas
\rem /s1 Paul's Last Visit to Troas; Paul's Final Visit to Troas; Paul's Farewell Visit to Troas; Eutychus Raised From the Dead at Troas
\p
\v 7 On the Sunday we had gatheredВҰ98524 together to breakВҰ98529 breadВҰ98530 together andВҰ98518 PaulВҰ98532 was discussingВҰ98533 many things with them. As he was scheduled to leave the next day, the meeting went on towards midnightВҰ98544
\v 8 andВҰ98546 thereВҰ98545 were many lampsВҰ98548 in the upperВҰ98552 roomВҰ98552 whereВҰ98553 weВҰ98554 had all gatheredВҰ98556.
\v 9 Now there was a youngВҰ98561 manВҰ98561 named EutychusВҰ98563 who was sittingВҰ98557 on the windowВҰ98567 sill, and as PaulВҰ98576 went on, he fell asleep and toppled down from the thirdВҰ98587 storey. The ones who reached him first thought he was deadВҰ98592,
\v 10 butВҰ98594 PaulВҰ98596 had comeВҰ98593 downstairs and bent over Eutychus and held him in hisВҰ98612 arms and saidВҰ98606 to the crowd, вҖңDon't worry, he's still alive.вҖқ
\v 11 ThenВҰ98617 Paul wentВҰ98633 back up and brokeВҰ98619 the breadВҰ98621 with the others, eating a little and continuing to talk with them untilВҰ98629 leaving at daybreakВҰ98630.
\v 12 The locals took the young man home andВҰ98643 were very relieved that he was alive.
\s1 Sailing from Troas to Miletus
\rem /s1 From Troas to Miletus; The Voyage from Troas to Miletus; Paul Meets the Ephesian Elders; Paul's Farewell to the Ephesian Elders
\p
\v 13 We went ahead to the shipВҰ98655 and departed for AssosВҰ98660 where it had been arranged that we'd pick up PaulВҰ98665 becauseВҰ98667 he wanted to walk thereВҰ98661.
\v 14 SoВҰ98678 when we met him at AssosВҰ98686, he boarded the ship andВҰ98678 we all sailed on to MityleneВҰ98691.
\v 15 After we left Mitylene, we were out from Kios the next day, in SamosВҰ98706 the day after that, andВҰ98692 thenВҰ98692 the following day we arrived at MiletusВҰ98717.
\v 16 PaulВҰ98722 had decided to sailВҰ98723 past EphesusВҰ98725 becauseВҰ98739 he was hurryingВҰ98738 to try to get to Yerushalem for the Day of Pentecost so he didn'tВҰ98727 want to spendВҰ98732 timeВҰ98732 in AsiaВҰ98737 \add Minor\add*.
\s1 Paul's farewell to the Ephesian elders
\rem /s1 Paul Speaks to the Ephesian Elders; Paul's Farewell Speech to the Elders of Ephesus
\p
\v 17 SoВҰ98756 while we were at MiletusВҰ98758, he sentВҰ98759 a message to EphesusВҰ98761 for the eldersВҰ98765 of the assemblyВҰ98767 to come to him.
\v 18 WhenВҰ98769 they arrivedВҰ98770, he told them, вҖңYou all know that from the very firstВҰ98785 dayВҰ98786 that I set footВҰ98790 in AsiaВҰ98793 \add Minor\add* andВҰ98769 for the entireВҰ98781 timeВҰ98807 that I was there
\v 19 I humbly served the \nd masterВҰ98812\nd* even through tearsВҰ98820 and trialsВҰ98822 when the Jews plotted to destroy me.
\v 20 ButВҰ98842 I didn'tВҰ98839 shrink back from teaching you everything thatВҰ98838 would help you, whether I was teaching in publicВҰ98845 or in individual homesВҰ98848.
\v 21 I explained to both Jews and GreeksВҰ98855 how they needed to turn their backs on their sins and towards \nd GodВҰ98859\nd* with faithВҰ98862 in ourВҰ98870 \nd masterВҰ98868 Yeshua\nd* the \nd messiahВҰ98873\nd*.
\p
\v 22 However the \nd spiritВҰ98882\nd* is now forcing me towards Yerushalem even though I don'tВҰ98894 know what will happen to me there.
\v 23 I just know that recently in everyВҰ98904 cityВҰ98906, the holy \nd spiritВҰ98900\nd* tells me that chains andВҰ98915 hardships are waiting for me.
\v 24 ButВҰ98949 I've never regarded my own life as being valuableвҖ”I only want to reach the end of my life having served in the way thatВҰ98954 the \nd masterВҰ98960 Yeshua\nd* instructed me to speak out the good messageВҰ98967 about God's graceВҰ98969.
\p
\v 25 SoВҰ98972 you see, I know that all of you from here where I passedВҰ98990 throughВҰ98990 proclaimingВҰ98991 God's kingdomВҰ98993, you will never see me again.
\v 26 That's why I'm declaring to all of youВҰ99002 todayВҰ99006 that I'm not guilty of your judgement
\v 27 becauseВҰ99018 I didn'tВҰ99017 avoid telling youВҰ99030 anything thatВҰ99020 I had from \nd GodВҰ99028\nd*.
\v 28 So now you elders look after your own lives and those of your flockВҰ99038 because the holy \nd spiritВҰ99043\nd* chose you as overseersВҰ99048 to shepherdВҰ99049 the assemblyВҰ99051 of God's people who he paid for with his very own bloodВҰ99062.
\v 29 I'm aware that afterВҰ99072 I leave, vicious wolvesВҰ99077 will come in amongstВҰ99079 youВҰ99080 and trying to steal the flockВҰ99084.
\v 30 Even some of youВҰ99087 will rise up andВҰ99085 teach a message that's warped butВҰ99085 which will draw some of the believers away to follow it,
\v 31 so take great care. Remember that for threeВҰ99105 years, I never stopped warning each of you along with my tearsВҰ99113
\v 32 so now I'm leaving you all in God's hands andВҰ99118 with the messageВҰ99130 of hisВҰ99133 graceВҰ99132 whichВҰ99134 is quite capable of helping you grow to receive the inheritanceВҰ99143 that's for all those who've been purified.
\p
\v 33 I never envied anyone's goldВҰ99155 or silverВҰ99152 or \add fancy\add* clothesВҰ99157
\v 34 and youВҰ99163 yourselvesВҰ99161 know that I laboured with my own handsВҰ99179 to cover my expenses and for those with me.
\v 35 Yes, I showedВҰ99185 you all that it's good to work and to take care of the weaker ones and to rememberВҰ99195 the messageВҰ99198 of the \nd masterВҰ99200 Yeshua\nd* when he saidВҰ99205 that it's better to be a giver than a taker.вҖқ
\p
\v 36 WhenВҰ99214 he'd finished speaking, Paul kneltВҰ99217 down andВҰ99214 prayedВҰ99224 with them all.
\v 37 EveryoneВҰ99238 was sobbing as theyВҰ99239 hugged andВҰ99232 kissed himВҰ99240
\v 38 because what he'd said about never seeing him again had really distressedВҰ99241 them. ThenВҰ99260 they accompaniedВҰ99259 him to hisВҰ99257 shipВҰ99265.
\c 21
\s1 Paul goes to Yerushalem
\rem /s1 On to Jerusalem; Paul Goes to Jerusalem; Paul's Journey to Jerusalem
\p
\v 1 WhenВҰ99268 itВҰ99269 was time for us to sail, weВҰ99285 left them and sailed directly across to CosВҰ99288 before going on to RhodesВҰ99295 the next dayВҰ99289 and thenВҰ99268 on to PataraВҰ99298.
\v 2 From there we foundВҰ99302 a shipВҰ99303 heading to PhoeniciaВҰ99306, so we boardedВҰ99307 that andВҰ99301 set off.
\v 3 After sighting CyprusВҰ99313 and thenВҰ99311 leaving itВҰ99317 behind on our left, we sailed on to SyriaВҰ99321 and docked thereВҰ99327 at the port of TyreВҰ99326 where the shipВҰ99331 had cargoВҰ99335 to be unloadedВҰ99333.
\v 4 We searched for the believers thereВҰ99343 andВҰ99338 thenВҰ99338 stayed on with them for sevenВҰ99345 daysВҰ99344. They were inspired by the \nd spiritВҰ99352\nd* to tell PaulВҰ99348 not to go to Yerushalem.
\v 5 Once our time was up there and everyone knew that weВҰ99369 were leaving, even the wivesВҰ99374 and childrenВҰ99376 accompaniedВҰ99370 us out of the cityВҰ99380 to the port. We all kneltВҰ99382 on the beach and prayedВҰ99390
\v 6 before we continued on and boarded our shipВҰ99402 and they wentВҰ99398 back to theirВҰ99407 own homesВҰ99408.
\p
\v 7 SoВҰ99410 we sailed from TyreВҰ99415 down to PtolemaisВҰ99419 where we were able to greetВҰ99421 the brothersВҰ99423 and sistersВҰ99423 and stay overnight with them.
\v 8 The next dayВҰ99430 we continued on to CaesareaВҰ99441 and ended up in Philip's houseВҰ99446. He was one of the \add original\add* sevenВҰ99454 \add men who had been given the responsibility of distributing aid\add*вҖ”a preacherВҰ99449 of the goodВҰ99449 messageВҰ99449, and we stayed with himВҰ99457.
\v 9 Philip had fourВҰ99464 unmarried daughtersВҰ99462 still at home, andВҰ99459 they shared messages from God.
\v 10 Several daysВҰ99471 later a man named AgabusВҰ99480 cameВҰ99473 from YudeaВҰ99477. He too shared messages from God
\v 11 and when he arrived, he picked up Paul's belt and tied it around his own feet and hands, telling them that the holy \nd spiritВҰ99510\nd* had told him that this is how the owner of the belt would be treated by the Jewish leaders in Yerushalem before they would then hand him over to the non-Jews to be dealt with.
\p
\v 12 WhenВҰ99536 we heardВҰ99537 this described, both we andВҰ99536 the localsВҰ99545 begged Paul not to go to Yerushalem
\v 13 but he answeredВҰ99556, вҖңOh come on, what's all this weepingВҰ99568 and carrying on that's breakingВҰ99571 myВҰ99572 heartВҰ99574? Actually I'm quite readyВҰ99587 not only to be tied up, but even to be killed in Yerushalem as a testimony to the \nd masterВҰ99595 Yeshua\nd*.вҖқ
\p
\v 14 WhenВҰ99600 we saw that we couldn't change his mind, we didn'tВҰ99598 say anything else, figuring out that whatever the \nd masterВҰ99608\nd* wills for the situation would happen,
\rem /s1 Paul Arrives at Jerusalem
\v 15 and so afterВҰ99616 theseВҰ99621 several daysВҰ99620, weВҰ99627 had gotten everything ready and started off for YerushalemВҰ99631.
\v 16 Some of the believers from CaesareaВҰ99639 accompanied us andВҰ99633 led us to the home of a man named MnasonВҰ99647 to stayвҖ”he was an older believer from CyprusВҰ99649.
\s1 Paul visits Yacob and makes a vow
\rem /s1 Paul's Arrival at Jerusalem; Paul Visits James at Jerusalem
\p
\v 17 WhenВҰ99653 we arrived at YerushalemВҰ99656, the brothersВҰ99662 andВҰ99653 sistersВҰ99662 there happily welcomedВҰ99658 us,
\v 18 and the next dayВҰ99663, we accompanied PaulВҰ99672 to go and see Yacob\f + \fr 21:18 \ft Yacob is commonly (but wrongly) called James in most older English Bibles.\f* and the eldersВҰ99681 of the assembly there.
\v 19 After greetingВҰ99685 them, Paul thenВҰ99683 described all the things that \nd GodВҰ99701\nd* had done among the non-Jews as he had served among them,
\v 20 and when they'd heardВҰ99711 all thatВҰ99732 they praisedВҰ99712 \nd GodВҰ99715\nd* and told Paul, вҖңBrother, you've noticed how many thousandsВҰ99724 of Jews have believedВҰ99733 \add in the messiah\add* butВҰ99710 they still strive to observeВҰ99721 \add Mosheh's\add* laws.
\v 21 ButВҰ99742 they've heard reports that you've been teachingВҰ99747 the Jews that live outside our country that they don't have to obey what Mosheh \add wrote\add*вҖ”telling them that they don't have to have theirВҰ99763 childrenВҰ99764 circumcisedВҰ99761 andВҰ99742 that they don't have to follow our \add Jewish\add* customsВҰ99769.
\v 22 What will happen \add now\add*, because \add the leaders here\add* will certainly hearВҰ99781 that youВҰ99784 have arrived?
\v 23 SoВҰ99786 here's what weВҰ99790 suggest that youВҰ99789 do: Four of our men are making a \add public\add* vow.
\v 24 Why don't you join theseВҰ99800 four and join them in the purificationВҰ99802 ceremony \add at the temple\add* and pay their expenses in getting your heads shaved. Then everyone will be able to see thatВҰ99824 it's false what they've heard aboutВҰ99826 you, because you \add clearly\add* still comply with \add Mosheh's\add* instructionsВҰ99825.
\v 25 And as for the believersВҰ99845 who are non-Jews, we've informed them of our recommendation that they should avoid anything that's been offered to an idolВҰ99870, avoid consuming bloodВҰ99873 and meat from strangledВҰ99875 animalsВҰ99875 and birds, and avoid sexualВҰ99877 immoralityВҰ99877.вҖқ
\rem /s1 Paul Is Arrested
\p
\v 26 So the next dayВҰ99887 PaulВҰ99880 took the \add four\add* menВҰ99883 for the purificationВҰ99890 ceremony in the templeВҰ99895 and there they announcedВҰ99896 the date when their vows would be fulfilledВҰ99898 and their sacrifices made.
\s1 Paul is captured inside the temple
\rem /s1 Paul Is Arrested in the Temple; Paul's work in Jerusalem
\p
\v 27 WhenВҰ99915 the sevenВҰ99919 daysВҰ99921 \add of the vow\add* were almost over, some Jews from \add the province of\add* AsiaВҰ99929 \add Minor\add* noticed Paul in the templeВҰ99936. They stirred up the crowdВҰ99946 andВҰ99915 grabbed hold of him,
\v 28 yelling out, вҖңMen of Yisrael. Help us here. This is the manВҰ99963 who's been teachingВҰ99981 all around the world against Yisrael and against \add Mosheh's\add* law and against this temple. What's more he broughtВҰ99986 non-Jews here into the temple and so has defiledВҰ99993 this holy place.вҖқ
\v 29 (\add They said this\add* becauseВҰ99999 they had previouslyВҰ100001 seenВҰ100001 TrofimusВҰ100002 from Ephesus in the cityВҰ100007 with PaulВҰ100019 and had assumed that he had broughtВҰ100017 him into the templeВҰ100016.)
\p
\v 30 SoВҰ100021 now the wholeВҰ100024 cityВҰ100023 was in an uproar, and the crowds rushed in, grabbed PaulВҰ100033, and draggedВҰ100034 him out of the temple and hurriedly closed the temple gates.
\v 31 They were ready to killВҰ100051 Paul, butВҰ100048 the commanderВҰ100055 of the Roman soldiers had heard that all Yerushalem was in an uproar.
\v 32 Taking some soldiers and officers, he immediatelyВҰ100064 ran down to the temple, and when the crowd saw the commanderВҰ100077 and the soldiers they stopped beating PaulВҰ100085.
\v 33 The commanderВҰ100090 came close and tookВҰ100091 hold of Paul and orderedВҰ100094 that he be tied up with a pair of chainsВҰ100096 while he tried to find out who he was and what he'd done wrong.
\v 34 Various people in the crowdВҰ100117 were shouting out different things, andВҰ100122 not being able to make any sense of it becauseВҰ100127 of all the commotionВҰ100129, the commanderВҰ100130 orderedВҰ100130 that Paul be taken into the barracksВҰ100135.
\v 35 WhenВҰ100137 they got to the stairsВҰ100142, the soldiersВҰ100150 had to lift himВҰ100147 up above their heads becauseВҰ100151 of the frenzy of the crowdВҰ100156,
\v 36 becauseВҰ100158 most of the peopleВҰ100162 were followingВҰ100157 and shouting out, вҖңDo away with himВҰ100167!вҖқ
\s1 Paul's defence
\rem /s1 Paul Speaks to the Crowd; Paul Defends Himself
\p
\v 37 As they were able to carry him into the fortress, PaulВҰ100175 called down to the commander, вҖңCan I sayВҰ100185 somethingВҰ100186 to youВҰ100188?вҖқ
\p вҖңYou speak Greek!вҖқ, replied the commander.
\v 38 вҖңAren't youВҰ100196 the Egyptian who stirred up a group of assassinsВҰ100215 a while back and led them out into the wildernessВҰ100210?вҖқ
\p
\v 39 вҖңNo, I'm a Jew from TarsusВҰ100227 in CilicaвҖ”a citizenВҰ100235 of an important cityВҰ100234,вҖқ saidВҰ100216 PaulВҰ100219. вҖңBut please, let me speakВҰ100243 to these peopleВҰ100246.вҖқ
\p
\v 40 The commander nodded, so the soldiers stoodВҰ100256 Paul on the stairsВҰ100259 where he gesturedВҰ100262 to the peopleВҰ100267. The crowd quietened down, andВҰ100249 so Paul spoke loudly in hisВҰ100248 HebrewВҰ100280 languageВҰ100281:
\c 22
\nb
\v 1 вҖңMen, brothersВҰ100284, andВҰ100285 fathersВҰ100286, listenВҰ100287 to what I have to say for myself.вҖқ
\v 2 WhenВҰ100296 they heardВҰ100295 him speaking HebrewВҰ100299, they became even more quietВҰ100305 as he continued,
\v 3 вҖңI am a Jew who grew up in this very cityВҰ100327 to study under GamalielВҰ100332. I've been raised accordingВҰ100335 to every part of ourВҰ100337 ancestralВҰ100338 law, working hard to obey \nd GodВҰ100343\nd* like all of youВҰ100347 here todayВҰ100350.
\v 4 I used to persecuteВҰ100356 the followers of вҖҳThe PathвҖҷ even to deathВҰ100359вҖ”tying up both men and womenВҰ100369 and handing them over to the prisonsВҰ100364
\v 5 as the Chief Priest and all the councilВҰ100383 of eldersВҰ100383 can tell \add you\add*. I took lettersВҰ100387 from them to our \add Jewish\add* brothersВҰ100393 in DamascusВҰ100396 when I went so that I could arrest the ones thereВҰ100402 and bringВҰ100398 them back here to Yerushalem to be punishedВҰ100410.
\s1 Paul explains about his conversion
\rem /s1 Paul Tells of His Conversion
\r (Acts 9:1-19; 26:12-18)
\p
\v 6 вҖңButВҰ100416 one time as I was travelling andВҰ100416 getting close to DamascusВҰ100419 by the middle of the day, suddenlyВҰ100424 a bright lightВҰ100432 from the skyВҰ100428 began to flashВҰ100429 around me
\v 7 andВҰ100442 I fell to the groundВҰ100441. I heardВҰ100443 a voiceВҰ100444 asking me, вҖҳSaul, Saul, why are youВҰ100451 persecutingВҰ100451 me?вҖҷ
\v 8 вҖҳWho are you, masterВҰ100459?вҖҷ I answeredВҰ100454. And the voice saidВҰ100460, вҖҳI am \nd Yeshua\nd*вҖ”the one from \nd NazarethВҰ100470\nd* that you are persecutingВҰ100473.вҖҷ
\v 9 The otherВҰ100488 people with me sawВҰ100482 the lightВҰ100481 butВҰ100475 didn'tВҰ100490 hear the voiceВҰ100489 that spoke to me.
\v 10 ThenВҰ100496 I asked, вҖҳWhat do I need to do, master?вҖҷ вҖҳGet up andВҰ100496 continue into DamascusВҰ100509,вҖҷ the master said. вҖҳWhenВҰ100496 you get thereВҰ100510, you'll be told everything that you've been assigned to do.вҖҷ
\v 11 But I couldn't see anything becauseВҰ100526 the brightness of the lightВҰ100530 \add had affected my eyes\add*, so my companions had to lead me by handВҰ100532 into DamascusВҰ100540.
\p
\v 12 вҖңIn Damascus there was a manВҰ100544 named AnaniasВҰ100541вҖ”a \add non-Jew\add* butВҰ100542 who was respected by the Jews there because he strove to obey \add Mosheh's\add* instructions about livingВҰ100555.
\v 13 Ananias came to where I was and standing by me saidВҰ100562, вҖңBrother SaulВҰ100564, receiveВҰ100566 your sightВҰ100566!вҖқ That very hourВҰ100570 I was able to see again and look at himВҰ100574
\v 14 and he saidВҰ100577, вҖҳThe \nd godВҰ100579\nd* of ourВҰ100582 ancestorsВҰ100581 has decided in advance to reveal hisВҰ100589 plans to you, and for you to seeВҰ100591 the sinless oneвҖ”to hearВҰ100595 him speaking
\v 15 because he wants you to inform peopleВҰ100607 everywhere what you've seenВҰ100610 and heardВҰ100612.
\v 16 SoВҰ100613 what else are you waitingВҰ100616 for? Get up andВҰ100613 wash away yourВҰ100623 sinsВҰ100622 by getting immersedВҰ100618 \add in water\add* as you request hisВҰ100629 forgiveness.вҖҷ
\s1 The crowd riots when Paul mentions preaching to non-Jews
\rem /s1 Paul Sent to the Gentiles; Paul's Call to Preach to the Gentiles
\p
\v 17 вҖңThenВҰ100631 when I returnedВҰ100633 to Yerushalem andВҰ100636 was prayingВҰ100637 in the templeВҰ100641, I fell into a tranceВҰ100645
\v 18 and saw \add @the master\add* telling me, вҖҳGet out of Yerushalem in a hurry becauseВҰ100659 theyВҰ100661 won'tВҰ100660 acceptВҰ100661 what you're teaching them about me.вҖҷ
\v 19 вҖҳ\nd MasterВҰ100669\nd*,вҖҷ I replied, вҖҳtheyВҰ100670 know that previously I was the one imprisoningВҰ100675 andВҰ100676 beatingВҰ100677 the people who believedВҰ100682 in youВҰ100684,
\v 20 and when StephenВҰ100690 was killed after teaching about youВҰ100693, it was me standing there and cheering on the ones executing himВҰ100710 as I held their coats for them.вҖҷ
\v 21 ThenВҰ100711 \add @the master\add* told me, вҖҳGet goingВҰ100715 now becauseВҰ100716 I'm sendingВҰ100722 youВҰ100724 away to the non-Jews.вҖҷ вҖқ
\rem /s1 Paul the Roman Citizen; Paul and the Roman Tribune
\p
\v 22 Until this point in his messageВҰ100732, the crowd had been listening to Paul, butВҰ100727 now they started shouting, вҖңDo away with this manВҰ100744! He doesn't deserve to live in this world!вҖқ
\v 23 Then they yelled and threw some of theirВҰ100758 clothesВҰ100759 down onto the ground and threw dust up into the air.
\rem /s1 Paul Reveals His Roman Citizenship
\v 24 So the commanderВҰ100770 ordered Paul to be broughtВҰ100771 inside into barracksВҰ100776 and ordered that he be floggedВҰ100778 and interrogatedВҰ100779 to determine what he'd done that would make the crowd react like that.
\v 25 ButВҰ100815 as they strappedВҰ100802 him down and stretchedВҰ100797 him out for the floggingВҰ100820, PaulВҰ100809 asked the centurionВҰ100807 standing there, вҖңIt is legal for you to flog a Roman citizen who hasn't even been tried?вҖқ
\p
\v 26 WhenВҰ100823 he heardВҰ100822 that, the centurionВҰ100825 went to the commanderВҰ100833 andВҰ100823 reportedВҰ100835, вҖңHow are we goingВҰ100840 to handle this, becauseВҰ100843 this manВҰ100844 is a Roman citizen?вҖқ
\p
\v 27 SoВҰ100850 the commanderВҰ100852 went in to where Paul was andВҰ100850 asked himВҰ100855, вҖңTell me the truth. Are youВҰ100860 a Roman citizen?вҖқ
\p вҖңYes I am,вҖқ saidВҰ100854 Paul.
\p
\v 28 вҖңYeah, andВҰ100872 I paid a lot for mine as well,вҖқ mocked the commanderВҰ100875.
\p вҖңActually mine is through birth,вҖқ PaulВҰ100890 responded.
\p
\v 29 At this point, the soldiers who were about to interrogateВҰ100906 Paul left the room, and even the commanderВҰ100909 was now afraidВҰ100911 after learningВҰ100912 that he'd had a Roman citizen tied down to be flogged.
\s1 Paul faces the Jewish council
\rem /s1 Paul's trials; Paul before the Council; Paul before the High Council; Before the Sanhedrin
\p
\v 30 The next dayВҰ100922, the Roman commanderВҰ100942 still wanted to knowВҰ100926 what was behind the anger of the Jews, so he had Paul releasedВҰ100936 from the cell, butВҰ100923 broughtВҰ100954 him down to a room where he'd orderedВҰ100942 the chiefВҰ100946 priestsВҰ100946 and the Jewish councilВҰ100951 to convene. Paul was given a seat
\c 23
\nb
\v 1 and looking directly at the councilВҰ100965 members saidВҰ100968, вҖңMen, brothersВҰ100970, all my life I have livedВҰ100975 before \nd GodВҰ100977\nd* as a goodВҰ100974 citizenВҰ100975 and with a clean conscienceВҰ100973.вҖқ
\v 2 ButВҰ100983 AnaniasВҰ100985 the chiefВҰ100984 priestВҰ100984 commandedВҰ100987 one of hisВҰ100992 companions to whack Paul on the mouthВҰ100994.
\v 3 вҖң\nd GodВҰ101008\nd* will strikeВҰ101004 you,вҖқ saidВҰ101003 PaulВҰ100997, вҖңyou grand show-off. You've been brought here to judge me as someone who knows the law andВҰ101011 yet you violateВҰ101020 the law by commandingВҰ101021 that I be hit in the face.вҖқ
\p
\v 4 But the others standing there saidВҰ101027, вҖңAre youВҰ101032 insultingВҰ101032 God's chiefВҰ101029 priestВҰ101029?вҖқ
\p
\v 5 вҖңBrothersВҰ101039,вҖқ said PaulВҰ101036, вҖңI didn'tВҰ101037 realise that he's the chiefВҰ101042 priestВҰ101042, becauseВҰ101044 the scriptures teach us not to speakВҰ101051 wronglyВҰ101052 of our leaders.вҖқ
\p
\v 6 ButВҰ101082 then, knowingВҰ101053 that the councilВҰ101071 consisted of some from the sect of the Sadducees and some from the Pharisees' party, PaulВҰ101056 continued loudly, вҖңMen, brothersВҰ101073, like my father, I'm a memberВҰ101075 of the Pharisees and I'm beingВҰ101086 tried today concerningВҰ101080 the hope and the resurrectionВҰ101083 of the deadВҰ101084!вҖқ
\p
\v 7 Well, as soon as he said this, the council was split as the Pharisees andВҰ101088 the Sadducees started arguing.
\v 8 (Sadducees say thatВҰ101123 the dead don't come back to life, and there's no messengersВҰ101117 and no spiritsВҰ101119, butВҰ101121 the Pharisees believe there is.)
\v 9 SoВҰ101126 thenВҰ101126 there was a big kerfuffle because some of the teachersВҰ101135 of the law spoke up for the Pharisees sayingВҰ101144, вҖңWe don't see anything wrong with this manВҰ101150. Maybe it was a spiritВҰ101154 or one \add of God's\add* messengersВҰ101158 that spoke to him.вҖқ
\p
\v 10 ButВҰ101162 the \add Roman\add* commanderВҰ101172 was afraidВҰ101169 that they might tear Paul apartВҰ101174 in the big argument, so he called for his soldiers to comeВҰ101184 down to uplift Paul andВҰ101162 return him to the barracksВҰ101196.
\p
\v 11 The followingВҰ101199 nightВҰ101200, the \nd masterВҰ101204\nd* appeared to Paul and told himВҰ101202, вҖңBe brave becauseВҰ101209 just like you testifiedВҰ101210 about me here in Yerushalem, so too you'll tell them about me in RomeВҰ101222.вҖқ
\s1 The plan to kill Paul
\rem /s1 The Plan to Kill Paul; The Plot to Kill Paul; The Plot against Paul's Life
\p
\v 12 The next dayВҰ101227, some of the Jews gatheredВҰ101231 informally andВҰ101226 pledged not to eatВҰ101244 or drinkВҰ101246 untilВҰ101247 they'd killed PaulВҰ101255.
\v 13 There were more than fortyВҰ101259 of them in this conspiracyВҰ101265,
\v 14 and they approachedВҰ101269 the chiefВҰ101271 priestsВҰ101271 and eldersВҰ101274 and told them, вҖңWe'veВҰ101276 made an oath to tasteВҰ101280 nothingВҰ101279 untilВҰ101283 we've killed PaulВҰ101288, otherwise we'll bring a curseВҰ101276 on ourselvesВҰ101278.
\v 15 SoВҰ101290 you guys assemble the councilВҰ101305 and reportВҰ101300 to the commanderВҰ101302 so thatВҰ101332 he'll bringВҰ101309 him down to you all as if you need more information about his actions, and then we'll have an opportunity to killВҰ101333 beforeВҰ101325 he gets here.
\p
\v 16 ButВҰ101351 a nephew of Paul had heardВҰ101339 about this ambushВҰ101348 andВҰ101351 went in to the barracksВҰ101356 to inform Paul.
\v 17 PaulВҰ101363 thenВҰ101361 calledВҰ101360 one of the Roman centurionsВҰ101366 andВҰ101361 told him to take the youngВҰ101370 manВҰ101370 to the commanderВҰ101376 becauseВҰ101378 he had somethingВҰ101381 to tell him.
\v 18 SoВҰ101385 the centurion took him to the commanderВҰ101391, explaining, вҖңThe prisonerВҰ101395 PaulВҰ101396, calledВҰ101397 me and askedВҰ101399 me to bring this youngВҰ101402 manВҰ101402 to you because he has somethingВҰ101408 to report to you.вҖқ
\p
\v 19 The commanderВҰ101418 took the young man by the handВҰ101415 and led himВҰ101416 into hisВҰ101416 private office and asked, вҖңWhat do youВҰ101428 have to tell me?вҖқ
\p
\v 20 вҖңThe Jews have decidedВҰ101436 to askВҰ101438 you,вҖқ he saidВҰ101431, вҖңthatВҰ101437 tomorrowВҰ101441 you bringВҰ101444 PaulВҰ101443 down to the councilВҰ101447 as if they wanted to question him further.
\v 21 ButВҰ101485 don'tВҰ101463 listen to them becauseВҰ101467 over fortyВҰ101473 of theirВҰ101469 menВҰ101471 will be lyingВҰ101466 in wait for him, and they've sworn not to eatВҰ101478 or drinkВҰ101480 untilВҰ101481 they've killed him. In fact, they're all set up already, just waitingВҰ101490 for your consent.вҖқ
\p
\v 22 The commanderВҰ101498 told the youngВҰ101501 manВҰ101501 not to tell anyoneВҰ101504 else about the ambush and dismissed him.
\s1 Paul is escorted away in the night
\rem /s1 Paul Is Sent to Caesarea; Paul Transferred to Caesarea; Paul Is Sent to Governor Felix; Paul Sent to Felix the Governor
\p
\v 23 ThenВҰ101511 the commander calledВҰ101512 in two of his centurionsВҰ101517 and ordered them to prepare two-hundred soldiers to travel as far as CaesareaВҰ101525, supported by seventyВҰ101528 mounted soldiers and two-hundred more with spearsВҰ101530. They were to be ready to leave by 9pm,
\v 24 along with a horse for PaulВҰ101543 to ride, andВҰ101538 were to get him safelyВҰ101544 to Governor FelixВҰ101546.
\v 25 Then the commander wroteВҰ101565 a letterВҰ101568 ready to take:
\p
\v 26 вҖңGreetings to the most excellentВҰ101581 Governor FelixВҰ101583 from Claudius LysiasВҰ101578.
\v 27 I'm writing to you about this manВҰ101586 who had been capturedВҰ101591 by the Jews here and they were about to kill him when I moved in with my soldiers because he is a Roman citizen.
\v 28 I wanted to knowВҰ101619 what they were accusing him of, so I took him down to theirВҰ101633 councilВҰ101632 meeting,
\v 29 butВҰ101645 I discovered that it was just some detail about theirВҰ101643 \add Jewish\add* law and nothingВҰ101644 that should result in deathВҰ101647 or imprisonment.
\v 30 ThenВҰ101654 when I learnt that they have a plot to try to ambush and kill him, I sentВҰ101668 him immediatelyВҰ101665 to you, and I'll order his accusersВҰ101674 to bring their case beforeВҰ101680 you.вҖқ
\p
\v 31 SoВҰ101685 the soldiersВҰ101686 carried out their instructions and took PaulВҰ101693 as far as AntipatrisВҰ101700 during the nightВҰ101697.
\v 32 The next morning the foot soldiers returnedВҰ101712 to the barracksВҰ101715, leaving the mounted soldiers to take himВҰ101710 on
\v 33 to CaesareaВҰ101720, where theyВҰ101727 presentedВҰ101727 PaulВҰ101730 to the governorВҰ101726 along with the letterВҰ101724.
\v 34 After reading the letter the governor askedВҰ101737 Paul what provinceВҰ101741 that he's from andВҰ101733 found out that he was from CiliciaВҰ101747.
\v 35 Then he orderedВҰ101763 Paul to be kept under guardВҰ101772 \add in the prison\add* in Herod's palace until he would hearВҰ101752 from him in the future once his accusersВҰ101758 got there.
\c 24
\s1 The Jews accuse Paul before Governor Felix
\rem /s1 The Case against Paul; Paul before Felix at Caesarea; Paul Appears before Felix; The Trial Before Felix
\p
\v 1 Five daysВҰ101778 later, AnaniasВҰ101782 the chiefВҰ101781 priestВҰ101781 arrived along with some eldersВҰ101785 andВҰ101787 an attorneyВҰ101788 named TertullosВҰ101789, to bring the charges againstВҰ101795 PaulВҰ101797 before Governor \add Felix\add*.
\v 2 Once he was calledВҰ101798 to speak, TertullosВҰ101804 beganВҰ101801 hisВҰ101800 accusationВҰ101802 of Paul:
\p вҖңWe have seen peaceВҰ101807 under your rule andВҰ101799 the helpful reformsВҰ101812 that this nationВҰ101816 has experienced through your provisionВҰ101821,
\v 3 most excellentВҰ101827 FelixВҰ101828, and weВҰ101826 gratefully welcomeВҰ101826 everything you've done and everywhere you've done itВҰ101826.
\v 4 But in orderВҰ101832 not to oblige you longer than necessary, in your gentlenessВҰ101847 we request you to listenВҰ101841 to our briefВҰ101844 statement.
\v 5 This manВҰ101851 here has been foundВҰ101848 to be a troublemaker, stirringВҰ101856 up riots among the Jews throughout the inhabitedВҰ101865 worldВҰ101865, and as a ring-leader of the Nazarite sect
\v 6 he even attemptedВҰ101876 to profaneВҰ101877 the templeВҰ101875 where weВҰ101880 were able to arrest him.
\v 7 в—ҳ
\v 8 When you examineВҰ101912 him yourselfВҰ101911 you'll discover all theseВҰ101915 things thatВҰ101917 we're accusingВҰ101919 him of.вҖқ
\v 9 The Jews who had come also affirmed all the accusations.
\s1 Paul's defence against the accusations
\rem /s1 Paul's Defense before Felix
\p
\v 10 SoВҰ101932 the governorВҰ101939 noddedВҰ101936 for PaulВҰ101935 to speakВҰ101940 andВҰ101932 he started,
\p вҖңI happily defendВҰ101956 myselfВҰ101955 today knowing that you have many yearsВҰ101943 of experience ruling \add in this region\add*.
\v 11 You can quickly establish that it was less than twelveВҰ101968 daysВҰ101966 ago that I arrived in Yerushalem to worship thereВҰ101964.
\v 12 They never foundВҰ101982 me in the templeВҰ101981 arguing with anyoneВҰ101985 or stirring up the crowdВҰ101991, andВҰ101977 nor was I doing that in the JewishВҰ101995 meetingВҰ101995 hallsВҰ101995 or anywhere in the cityВҰ101999
\v 13 and so they can't provide evidence to youВҰ102005 to support any of their accusationsВҰ102011.
\v 14 However, I must confessВҰ102013 that I follow вҖҳThe PathвҖҷ that theyВҰ102022 call a sect whichВҰ102021 serves the \nd GodВҰ102028\nd* of our ancestorsВҰ102027 andВҰ102035 believesВҰ102029 everything in \add Mosheh's\add* law as well as the writings of the prophetsВҰ102039.
\v 15 We put our trust in the same God thatВҰ102047 they themselvesВҰ102049 follow, and we all anticipate a resurrectionВҰ102052 of those who serve God and those who don't.
\v 16 Because of this, I also strive to maintain a clean conscienceВҰ102067 in everythingВҰ102077, before \nd GodВҰ102072\nd* andВҰ102073 the peopleВҰ102075.
\p
\v 17 After several yearsВҰ102079 away, I arrivedВҰ102089 \add in Yerushalem\add* bringing offeringsВҰ102091 to help myВҰ102088 own people andВҰ102090 before God.
\v 18 That was when theyВҰ102095 foundВҰ102095 me in the templeВҰ102100 after going through the purificationВҰ102097 ceremony, and without either a crowdВҰ102103 or a commotionВҰ102106 around me.
\v 19 ButВҰ102120 there were some Jews from \add the province of\add* AsiaВҰ102112 \add Minor\add* who are the ones who should be appearing here beforeВҰ102117 youВҰ102118, andВҰ102120 they should be the ones accusingВҰ102121 me if they could find anythingВҰ102123 againstВҰ102125 me.
\v 20 Even theseВҰ102130 ones here now shouldВҰ102131 explain what their councilВҰ102142 foundВҰ102134 me guilty of,
\v 21 other than my calling out thatВҰ102148 I was beingВҰ102160 judgedВҰ102160 because I believe in the resurrectionВҰ102157 of the deadВҰ102158.
\p
\v 22 But FelixВҰ102171 who was already familiar with followers of вҖҳThe PathвҖҷ, announced that the trial would be adjourned until Commander LysiasВҰ102182 arrived when he would investigateВҰ102186 further.
\v 23 He ordered the centurionВҰ102194 to keep Paul confined, butВҰ102200 under relaxedВҰ102201 conditions and allowing any of hisВҰ102207 friends to bring him anything he needed.
\s1 Paul speaks to the governor and his wife
\rem /s1 Paul Held in Custody; Paul before Felix and Drusilla
\p
\v 24 However, several daysВҰ102214 later FelixВҰ102219 returned there, \add this time\add* with his wifeВҰ102224 DrusillaВҰ102221 who was Jewish. He sentВҰ102229 for PaulВҰ102231 andВҰ102232 listened to himВҰ102234 explain about faithВҰ102241 in the \nd messiahВҰ102238\nd*.
\v 25 ButВҰ102248 when the subject turned to righteousnessВҰ102246 and self-control and the comingВҰ102255 judgementВҰ102253, FelixВҰ102262 became very uncomfortable and told him, вҖңThat's enough for now. If I have time in the future, I'll send for you.вҖқ
\v 26 However he was also hopingВҰ102277 that PaulВҰ102284 would give him moneyВҰ102279, so he often sent for him and spoke with him.
\p
\v 27 This went on for twoВҰ102296 yearsВҰ102296, until Felix was replaced as governor by PorciusВҰ102303 FestusВҰ102304, butВҰ102297 wantingВҰ102305 to stay in the good books of the Jews, Felix left PaulВҰ102317 confined.
\c 25
\s1 Tried yet again, Paul appeals to Caesar
\rem /s1 The Trial Before Festus; Paul Appeals to the Emperor; Paul Appears before Festus
\p
\v 1 After FestusВҰ102319 had been in the area for threeВҰ102326 daysВҰ102327, he made the uphill trip from CaesareaВҰ102332 to Yerushalem.
\v 2 There the chiefВҰ102340 priestsВҰ102340 and the Jewish leadersВҰ102343 repeated their case againstВҰ102346 PaulВҰ102348, and theyВҰ102350 imploredВҰ102350 Festus,
\v 3 asking as a special favourВҰ102353, that he would order Paul to be sent to Yerushalem (because they wanted to ambushВҰ102363 and killВҰ102365 him on the wayВҰ102369).
\v 4 ButВҰ102383 FestusВҰ102373 replied thatВҰ102370 he'd keep PaulВҰ102377 in CaesareaВҰ102380 andВҰ102383 he was heading back there soon,
\v 5 so he told them, вҖңSome of your leaders can go there with me, and if the manВҰ102404 has done anythingВҰ102399 wrong, they can explain their accusationsВҰ102407 there.вҖқ
\p
\v 6 After staying seven or eightВҰ102417 daysВҰ102413 in Yerushalem, Festus and company travelled back to CaesareaВҰ102422, and the next dayВҰ102424 he satВҰ102426 at the judge's bench and orderedВҰ102430 that PaulВҰ102432 be broughtВҰ102434 in.
\v 7 WhenВҰ102436 he arrivedВҰ102435, the Jews who'd comeВҰ102443 from Yerushalem stoodВҰ102438 facing Paul andВҰ102446 presented many heavyВҰ102447 chargesВҰ102448 whichВҰ102454 theyВҰ102456 weren't able to prove.
\v 8 PaulВҰ102460 defendedВҰ102461 himself, stating that he hadn't sinnedВҰ102478 against any Jewish law or against the templeВҰ102473, nor against any Roman law.
\p
\v 9 However, FestusВҰ102480 wanted to be able to grantВҰ102488 a favourВҰ102487 to the Jews, so in response to PaulВҰ102491 he asked, вҖңAre you willingВҰ102493 to be returned to Yerushalem so that I can judgeВҰ102501 you about theseВҰ102499 things thereВҰ102497?вҖқ
\p
\v 10 вҖңI'm here facing Caesar's representative,вҖқ PaulВҰ102507 replied. вҖңand it's quite appropriateВҰ102517 for me to be judgedВҰ102518 here. I've done nothingВҰ102520 wrongВҰ102522 to these Jews as youВҰ102525 can no doubt see for yourself.
\v 11 If I had done anything wrongВҰ102533, anything worthyВҰ102535 of the death sentence, then I'm ready to accept death. On the otherВҰ102544 hand, if none of their accusationsВҰ102549 are true, no one can hand me over to them. I appeal to CaesarВҰ102557.вҖқ
\p
\v 12 So FestusВҰ102561 conferred with his legal counselВҰ102566 and answeredВҰ102567, вҖңWell, you've appealedВҰ102569 to Caesar so you'll go to Caesar!вҖқ
\s1 King Agrippa wants to hear from Paul
\rem /s1 Festus Consults King Agrippa; Paul before Agrippa and Bernice
\p
\v 13 Several daysВҰ102573 later, KingВҰ102579 AgrippaВҰ102577 andВҰ102580 \add his sister\add* BerniceВҰ102581 arrivedВҰ102582 in CaesareaВҰ102585 to meet FestusВҰ102589.
\v 14 As theyВҰ102594 \add had planned to\add* stay on for a few daysВҰ102593, FestusВҰ102598 mentioned about PaulВҰ102605 to the kingВҰ102600, telling him, вҖңThere'sВҰ102609 a prisonerВҰ102613 here that FelixВҰ102612 left behind.
\v 15 When I was in Yerushalem, the chiefВҰ102623 priestsВҰ102623 andВҰ102624 Jewish eldersВҰ102626 reportedВҰ102620 to me, wanting a convictionВҰ102632 of this man.
\v 16 I told them that it's not the Roman way to convict someone until they've been able to faceВҰ102654 their accusers andВҰ102660 make their defenceВҰ102661 against the accusations.
\v 17 SoВҰ102667 as soon as they arrived here, on the very next dayВҰ102675 I satВҰ102677 on the judge's bench and orderedВҰ102681 the manВҰ102684 to be broughtВҰ102682 in
\v 18 that they were accusingВҰ102689, but they didn'tВҰ102690 raise even one of the chargesВҰ102691 that I expected.
\v 19 Instead theyВҰ102708 raised some issues about theirВҰ102705 own beliefs andВҰ102712 about some dead person called \nd Yeshua\nd* that PaulВҰ102720 reckoned was still livingВҰ102721.
\v 20 I was puzzled about this debateВҰ102730 andВҰ102723 asked him if he wanted to be judgedВҰ102740 about these things in Yerushalem.
\v 21 But PaulВҰ102745 appealedВҰ102746 to be kept safe from them until he could face the emperor, so I orderedВҰ102755 him to be kept \add in prison\add* until I can send him to Rome.вҖқ
\p
\v 22 вҖңI'd quite like to hear him myselfВҰ102773,вҖқ AgrippaВҰ102765 said.
\rem /s1 Paul Before Agrippa; Paul Speaks to Agrippa; Paul Brought before Agrippa
\p вҖңWell, tomorrow,вҖқ replied FestusВҰ102769, вҖңyou'll be able to hear from him.вҖқ
\p
\v 23 SoВҰ102784 the next dayВҰ102783, \add King\add* AgrippaВҰ102788 and BerniceВҰ102791 formally arrived with all their attendants and entered the auditoriumВҰ102800 to greet the commandersВҰ102804 and the prominentВҰ102809 menВҰ102806 of the cityВҰ102812, and then FestusВҰ102816 orderedВҰ102814 for PaulВҰ102819 to be broughtВҰ102817 in.
\v 24 FestusВҰ102823 started, вҖңKingВҰ102825 AgrippaВҰ102824 and everyone presentВҰ102829, observeВҰ102832 the prisoner who a multitudeВҰ102839 of Jews pleadedВҰ102842 with me about both in Yerushalem and here, that he doesn't deserve to still be alive.
\v 25 ButВҰ102870 I haven't discovered anything that he's done that's worthyВҰ102863 of a deathВҰ102865 sentence, and since he himselfВҰ102869 appealedВҰ102874 to the emperor, I judgedВҰ102877 that that's where he should be sent.
\v 26 The problem is that I don'tВҰ102888 have any charge to write to my masterВҰ102887 and so I've broughtВҰ102892 the prisoner out in front of you so that after you examineВҰ102904 him, I might have somethingВҰ102908 I can write,
\v 27 becauseВҰ102912 itВҰ102914 doesn't seem logical to me to transport a prisonerВҰ102916 \add to Rome\add* if there's no chargesВҰ102922 specified againstВҰ102920 himВҰ102921.вҖқ
\c 26
\s1 Paul's defence before Festus and Agrippa
\rem /s1 Paul Defends Himself before Agrippa
\p
\v 1 So then AgrippaВҰ102924 told PaulВҰ102928, вҖңOkay, youВҰ102931 can give your side now then.вҖқ
\m So Paul gestured with his handВҰ102942 andВҰ102925 began:
\p
\v 2 вҖңConcerningВҰ102944 all the charges whichВҰ102946 have been brought against me by the Jews, KingВҰ102950 AgrippaВҰ102951, I considerВҰ102952 myselfВҰ102953 fortunate
\v 3 because you're an expert on Jewish customsВҰ102976 and issues, so I ask you to listenВҰ102985 to me patientlyВҰ102984.
\p
\v 4 вҖңAll the Jews know about my early life, from my upbringing in my own countryВҰ103001 andВҰ103004 then in Yerushalem.
\v 5 They also know, and could even testifyВҰ103015 to you if theyВҰ103014 would admit it, that I followed ourВҰ103022 religiousВҰ103023 laws very closely as a memberВҰ103025 of the Pharisees partyВҰ103025.
\v 6 Yet now I stand judgedВҰ103042 for believing in the same hope as our ancestorsВҰ103034вҖ”that hope promisedВҰ103036 by our \nd GodВҰ103040\nd*
\v 7 who we twelveВҰ103046 tribesВҰ103046 diligently serve dayВҰ103052 andВҰ103051 nightВҰ103050 in order to obtainвҖ”the hope, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, for whichВҰ103044 I'm beingВҰ103061 indictedВҰ103061.
\v 8 So why do youВҰ103072 all find itВҰ103070 unbelievableВҰ103069 that \nd GodВҰ103075\nd* can raise the deadВҰ103076?
\p
\v 9 вҖңI too \add originally\add* thought itВҰ103090 necessaryВҰ103090 to do many things to oppose the cause of this \nd Yeshua\nd* from \nd NazarethВҰ103089\nd*.
\v 10 So in Yerushalem I worked to have many of these innocent believers lockedВҰ103109 up in prisonВҰ103108 with the authorityВҰ103114 of the chiefВҰ103113 priestsВҰ103113, or if they were to be killedВҰ103116, I would add my vote againstВҰ103119 them.
\v 11 And in all the JewishВҰ103126 meetingВҰ103126 hallsВҰ103126, \add when I found believers\add* I punishedВҰ103128 them and forced them to curse \add God\add* and treated them with extreme anger, even travelling to further away towns.
\s1 Paul tells about his commission
\rem /s1 Paul Tells of His Conversion
\rem /r (Acts 9:1-19; 22:6-16)
\p
\v 12 вҖңSo it was one time travelling to DamascusВҰ103149 carrying permissionВҰ103153 letters from the chiefВҰ103157 priestsВҰ103157
\v 13 that in the middleВҰ103159 of the dayВҰ103158, \add вүҲyour majesty\add*, I sawВҰ103163 a bright lightВҰ103173 from the skyвҖ”even brighter than the sunВҰ103170вҖ”and it shoneВҰ103171 on me and my companions.
\v 14 All of us fell down to the groundВҰ103186 andВҰ103180 I heardВҰ103187 a voiceВҰ103188 speaking to me in HebrewВҰ103196 sayingВҰ103190, вҖҳSaul, Saul, why are you persecutingВҰ103202 me? Life will be difficult for you if you resist me.вҖҷ
\p
\v 15 вҖҳWho are you, master?вҖҷ, I asked.
\p вҖңAnd the master respondedВҰ103210, вҖҳI am \nd Yeshua\nd*, the one you'reВҰ103212 persecutingВҰ103223.
\v 16 Now get up, becauseВҰ103234 I let you see me in order to appointВҰ103237 you as my servant and my witnessВҰ103242вҖ”to tell the people what you've seen and what you will be shown.
\v 17 I will rescueВҰ103251 you from your own peopleВҰ103255 and from the non-Jews that I'm sendingВҰ103265 you out to,
\v 18 to open their minds and for them to turnВҰ103274 back from darknessВҰ103276 to lightВҰ103278 and from Satan'sВҰ103284 powerВҰ103282 to \nd GodВҰ103287\nd*, so thatВҰ103299 they can be forgivenВҰ103291 for their sinsВҰ103292 and receiveВҰ103289 an inheritance amongВҰ103295 the ones who've been made guiltless by their faithВҰ103298 in me.вҖҷ
\s1 Paul tells about his ministry
\rem /s1 Paul Tells of His Work; Paul Tells of His Preaching
\p
\v 19 вҖңSo then, KingВҰ103303 AgrippaВҰ103304, I couldn't disobey that visionВҰ103310
\v 20 so I preached firstВҰ103315 to those in DamascusВҰ103314 and then in Yerushalem and all of YudeaВҰ103327, and then in the towns of the non-Jews. I preached about turning from their sins and turning back to \nd GodВҰ103339\nd*, and then actually living like people who had repentedВҰ103334.
\v 21 It was because of theseВҰ103346 things that the Jews grabbed me in the templeВҰ103356 and tried to do me in.
\v 22 SoВҰ103360 it is that with God's helpВҰ103359 untilВҰ103367 this very dayВҰ103369 I have stoodВҰ103371 testifyingВҰ103372 to commoners and leaders, teaching nothingВҰ103378 other than what Mosheh and the prophetsВҰ103384 had already written that would happenвҖ”
\v 23 that the \nd messiahВҰ103393\nd* would \add come and\add* sufferВҰ103391 and as the firstВҰ103395 of the deadВҰ103398 to come back to life, he is goingВҰ103400 to be proclaimingВҰ103402 lightВҰ103399 to both Jews and non-Jews.вҖқ
\rem /s1 Paul Appeals to Agrippa to Believe
\p
\v 24 ThenВҰ103410 speaking about Paul's defenceВҰ103412, Governor FestusВҰ103414 said, вҖңPaul, you're stark, ravingВҰ103420 mad! All your education has turned you into an idiot.вҖқ
\p
\v 25 ButВҰ103440 PaulВҰ103432 said, вҖңI haven't gone mad, most excellentВҰ103436 FestusВҰ103437, butВҰ103438 I'm speakingВҰ103443 the truthВҰ103439 in all seriousness.
\v 26 The king knows what I'm talkingВҰ103454 about and that's why I'm speaking boldlyВҰ103453, becauseВҰ103445 none of these things were done in a cornerВҰ103467 and I'm sure that none of it has escapedВҰ103455 his noticeВҰ103455.
\v 27 KingВҰ103471 AgrippaВҰ103473, do you believe what the prophetsВҰ103475 \add wrote\add*? Yes, I'm sure you do.вҖқ
\p
\v 28 ButВҰ103480 AgrippaВҰ103481 answered PaulВҰ103484, вҖңDo you think you can talk me into becoming a followerВҰ103491 of the messiahВҰ103491 in just that short timeВҰ103487?вҖқ
\p
\v 29 вҖңI hope to \nd GodВҰ103502\nd*вҖқ, said PaulВҰ103496, вҖңwhether it takes a short time or a long time, that both you andВҰ103495 the others listening todayВҰ103519 will becomeВҰ103520 just like me exceptВҰ103527 for theseВҰ103530 chains.вҖқ
\p
\v 30 Then the kingВҰ103538 and the governorВҰ103541 both stood, along with BerniceВҰ103544 and the others sittingВҰ103547 with them
\v 31 and as they left they were sayingВҰ103554 to each other, вҖңThat manВҰ103566 hasn't done anything deserving of deathВҰ103558 or imprisonment.вҖқ
\p
\v 32 вҖңYes, he could have been set free,вҖқ replied AgrippaВҰ103568, вҖңif he hadn't appealedВҰ103580 to CaesarВҰ103581.вҖқ
\c 27
\s1 Paul is escorted off overseas
\rem /s1 Paul Sails for Rome; Paul's journey to Rome
\p
\v 1 SoВҰ103583 when itВҰ103584 was considered the right season to sail to ItalyВҰ103590, PaulВҰ103595 andВҰ103596 some otherВҰ103598 prisonersВҰ103599 were put under the guard of a centurionВҰ103600 named Julius (from the AugustanВҰ103605 Regiment).
\v 2 We all boardedВҰ103606 on a shipВҰ103608 from AdramyttiumВҰ103609 that was about to sail to various placesВҰ103618 alongВҰ103615 the coast of AsiaВҰ103617 \add Minor\add*. AristarchusВҰ103623, a Macedonian man from ThessalonicaВҰ103626, was with us as weВҰ103619 departed.
\p
\v 3 The next dayВҰ103629 weВҰ103630 docked at Tsidon where Julius very kindly allowed PaulВҰ103638 to visit some of his friendsВҰ103643 so they could provide for his needs.
\v 4 WhenВҰ103648 weВҰ103650 left again, the ship stayed between CyprusВҰ103652 andВҰ103648 the mainland becauseВҰ103653 of the unfavourable windsВҰ103656,
\v 5 thenВҰ103660 after sailing past CiliciaВҰ103665 andВҰ103666 PamfyliaВҰ103667, weВҰ103669 docked at MyraВҰ103673 in \add the province\add* of LyciaВҰ103675.
\v 6 There the centurionВҰ103680 foundВҰ103678 a shipВҰ103681 from AlexandriaВҰ103682 that was sailingВҰ103683 to ItalyВҰ103686, so he boarded us on that.
\p
\v 7 After many daysВҰ103695 of slow and difficultВҰ103698 sailingВҰ103696, we came alongside CnidusВҰ103702 butВҰ103694 the windВҰ103707 wasn't helpful to us, so we sailedВҰ103708 across to CreteВҰ103710 and along the cape of Salmone.
\v 8 We sailed alongВҰ103715 itВҰ103716 with difficultyВҰ103713 until weВҰ103717 cameВҰ103717 to a placeВҰ103719 calledВҰ103721 вҖҳFair HavensвҖҷ whichВҰ103724 was near the cityВҰ103727 of Lasea.
\p
\v 9 A lot of timeВҰ103732 had now elapsedВҰ103733 andВҰ103734 the voyageВҰ103739 was starting to become dangerousВҰ103737 becauseВҰ103740 we were already heading into winter. PaulВҰ103749 advisedВҰ103747 those in charge,
\v 10 telling them, вҖңMen, I perceiveВҰ103753 that we're going to encounter a lot of damageВҰ103756 on this voyageВҰ103777, with loss not only of the cargoВҰ103765 and the shipВҰ103768, butВҰ103757 also ourВҰ103773 livesВҰ103772.вҖқ
\v 11 ButВҰ103783 the centurionВҰ103780 was persuadedВҰ103788 by the shipВҰ103785 ownerВҰ103785 andВҰ103783 the captainВҰ103782, ratherВҰ103787 than by what PaulВҰ103793 had said.
\v 12 They realised that this harbour wasn't suitable to winter in, so the majority suggested leaving thereВҰ103807 with the expectation of beingВҰ103799 able to get to CreteВҰ103819 to winter in the harbour at PhoenixВҰ103815 (which was open to both the southwestВҰ103822 andВҰ103823 the northwestВҰ103825).
\s1 The severe storm at sea
\rem /s1 The Storm at Sea
\p
\v 13 WhenВҰ103828 a southВҰ103829 windВҰ103829 started blowing gentlyВҰ103826, they thought they could make it, so they pulled in the anchor andВҰ103828 sailed alongВҰ103836 close to CreteВҰ103838.
\v 14 HoweverВҰ103851, a short while later the windВҰ103847 turned to a violent north-easter whichВҰ103849 forced us out to sea.
\v 15 The shipВҰ103855 was driven by the windВҰ103861 and unable to tack to face into it, so the sailors gaveВҰ103862 up and just let it be driven.
\v 16 As we passed a small islandВҰ103864 calledВҰ103868 ClaudaВҰ103869, we got a brief break andВҰ103865 were able to resecure the lifeboatВҰ103877
\v 17 and thenВҰ103887 bring it up on board. ThenВҰ103887 ropes were used to wrap around the ship in case it were to run agroundВҰ103892 into the shallowsВҰ103890 at SyrtisВҰ103891 and the gear was loweredВҰ103893,\f + \fr 27:17 \ft It's not certain what was meant hereвҖ”it might have meant lowering the sails further to catch less wind or even lowering the mast, or else letting out the sea anchor to help keep the back of the ship facing the wind.\f* allowing the wind to driveВҰ103897 the ship alongВҰ103897.
\v 18 We were violentlyВҰ103898 tossedВҰ103901 around by the stormВҰ103901, andВҰ103900 the next dayВҰ103903 the crew started \add lightening the ship by\add* tipping \add some of the cargo\add* overboard.
\v 19 By the thirdВҰ103909 dayВҰ103909, the sailors themselves \add in desperation\add* were even throwing some of the ship's gear overboard.
\v 20 We didn't see either the sunВҰ103919 or the starsВҰ103921 for several more daysВҰ103925вҖ”it wasn't a minor stormВҰ103926 by any meansвҖ”andВҰ103927 by thenВҰ103918 any remaining hope thatВҰ103936 we had \add of staying alive\add* disappeared
\v 21 and no one had eaten or drunk much at all.
\p ThenВҰ103940 PaulВҰ103947 stoodВҰ103945 up in the middle of them and saidВҰ103951, вҖңWell, you should have listened to me after all and not left CreteВҰ103962, so now we have this damageВҰ103966 and loss.
\v 22 Nevertheless I think we can all cheerВҰ103976 up becauseВҰ103978 not a single lifeВҰ103979 will be lostвҖ”only the shipВҰ103987вҖ”
\v 23 becauseВҰ103989 last nightВҰ103994 one of the messengersВҰ104005 of the \nd GodВҰ103998\nd* that I serve came and stoodВҰ103988 beside me
\v 24 and told me not to be afraid because I would indeed get to standВҰ104013 before CaesarВҰ104010 and that \nd GodВҰ104019\nd* has grantedВҰ104016 your lives to me as well.
\v 25 SoВҰ104025 cheerВҰ104026 up, fellows, becauseВҰ104029 I'm certain that \nd GodВҰ104031\nd* will carry out what was told to me
\v 26 even though we'll runВҰ104048 agroundВҰ104048 onto an islandВҰ104042 first.вҖқ
\rem /s1 The Shipwreck
\p
\v 27 So it happened that in the middleВҰ104061 of our fourteenthВҰ104051 night of beingВҰ104055 blown across the AdriaticВҰ104059 Sea, the sailorsВҰ104066 suspectedВҰ104064 that we were nearing land.
\v 28 They dropped a weighted line and measured the ocean depth at around 40 metres and thenВҰ104074 a bit later it was down to 30 metres.
\v 29 Worrying that the ship might runВҰ104102 agroundВҰ104102 on roughВҰ104099 \add rocks\add*, they threw out fourВҰ104108 anchorsВҰ104107 from the sternВҰ104105 as they hoped that daylight would come quickly.
\v 30 ThenВҰ104113 the sailorsВҰ104114 loweredВҰ104122 the lifeboatВҰ104124 as if planning to pull out some anchorsВҰ104133 from the bow, butВҰ104113 really planning to desert the shipВҰ104120.
\v 31 However PaulВҰ104138 told the centurionВҰ104140 andВҰ104141 the soldiersВҰ104143 that if the sailors didn'tВҰ104145 remainВҰ104147 with the shipВҰ104150, everybody couldn't be sure to be savedВҰ104153,
\v 32 so the soldiersВҰ104159 cut the ropesВҰ104162 attaching the lifeboatВҰ104164 andВҰ104165 allowedВҰ104166 it to runВҰ104168 agroundВҰ104168.
\p
\v 33 As they waited for the daylight, PaulВҰ104179 encouraged them all to eat something, sayingВҰ104183, вҖңTodayВҰ104185 is our fourteenthВҰ104184 day andВҰ104170 you've had nothingВҰ104190 to eat. As we're waitingВҰ104187,
\v 34 I urge you to eat something. This will help you to have strength because none of you are going to drown.вҖқ
\v 35 Having saidВҰ104220 that, he gaveВҰ104226 thanksВҰ104226 to \nd GodВҰ104229\nd* in front of everyone, andВҰ104221 breaking some breadВҰ104225, started eatingВҰ104235 it.
\v 36 They all cheeredВҰ104236 up andВҰ104237 also started eating.
\v 37 There were twoВҰ104260 hundredВҰ104260 andВҰ104249 seventy-six of them on the shipВҰ104258,
\v 38 andВҰ104265 when they'd all eaten what they wanted, they lightenedВҰ104268 the shipВҰ104270 more by throwingВҰ104271 their wheatВҰ104273 into the seaВҰ104276.
\s1 The ship runs aground
\rem /s1 The Shipwreck
\p
\v 39 Once it becameВҰ104280 light, they saw thatВҰ104294 they were close to shoreВҰ104291 in a bay butВҰ104278 didn'tВҰ104283 recogniseВҰ104285 the place. After some discussion, they decided to try to save the shipВҰ104304
\v 40 so they cut away the anchorsВҰ104307 that were holding them in the seaВҰ104313 andВҰ104305 untied the rudderВҰ104319 \add handles\add*. ThenВҰ104305 raising the foresailВҰ104323, they let the windВҰ104324 blow them into the shoreВҰ104329.
\v 41 ButВҰ104338 they hit a bank with ocean on both sides of it and the ship ran agroundВҰ104335. The bow of the ship was completely stuckВҰ104343 butВҰ104331 the sternВҰ104349 was beingВҰ104350 broken up by the forceВҰ104354 of the ocean.
\p
\v 42 At this point the soldiersВҰ104359 decided that theyВҰ104365 should killВҰ104365 the prisonersВҰ104364 in case any of them decided to swim away andВҰ104358 escapeВҰ104369,
\v 43 butВҰ104372 the centurionВҰ104373 wanted to keep PaulВҰ104377 safe so he vetoed that plan. He commandedВҰ104384 those who could swim to jump off and swim in to shore,
\v 44 and for the othersВҰ104407 to grab \add floating\add* planksВҰ104405 or something off the shipВҰ104413 \add thatВҰ104410 would float\add*, and so everyoneВҰ104403 got safelyВҰ104418 onto the beach.
\c 28
\s1 On the island of Malta
\rem /s1 In Malta; Ashore on Malta; Paul on the Island of Malta
\p
\v 1 Once everyone was safe, weВҰ104426 discovered that the islandВҰ104430 is calledВҰ104431 Malta.
\v 2 And the people there showed incredible kindnessВҰ104440 to us as theyВҰ104447 welcomed us and lit a fireВҰ104445, as it started raining again and was very coldВҰ104458.
\v 3 However when PaulВҰ104462 was helping to pick up sticksВҰ104463 and putting them on the fireВҰ104473, a viperВҰ104474 was driven out by the heat and clampedВҰ104481 its jaws down on hisВҰ104485 handВҰ104484.
\v 4 WhenВҰ104487 the islanders sawВҰ104488 the snake hanging from his handВҰ104496 they decided that he must be a murdererВҰ104503 who had survived the shipwreck butВҰ104487 now fate had finally decided his time was up.
\v 5 However, Paul just shook the snake off into the fireВҰ104527 and wasn't harmed.
\v 6 The locals were waitingВҰ104547 for his arm to swellВҰ104538 up or for him to fall down deadВҰ104542, butВҰ104532 after a while when nothingВҰ104550 happened they changedВҰ104555 theirВҰ104555 mindsВҰ104555 and decided that instead, he must be a godВҰ104562.
\p
\v 7 The area that we had beached in belonged to the leaderВҰ104573 of the islandВҰ104575 named PubliusВҰ104577. He welcomed us andВҰ104564 looked after us for threeВҰ104581 daysВҰ104582,
\v 8 butВҰ104587 while we were there, his fatherВҰ104589 got sick with dysenteryВҰ104594 and feverВҰ104592. PaulВҰ104601 went in and placing his handsВҰ104608 on him, prayedВҰ104604 for him and healedВҰ104610 him.
\v 9 As a result of thatВҰ104619, anyone on the whole islandВҰ104624 who was sick came andВҰ104613 was cured
\v 10 and so the people brought us many gifts and when we left, they supplied us with provisions.
\s1 Sailing from Malta to Rome
\rem /s1 Arrival at Rome; From Malta to Rome; Paul Arrives at Rome
\p
\v 11 After threeВҰ104649 monthsВҰ104650 weВҰ104652 were able to leave on an AlexandrianВҰ104659 shipВҰ104654 that had winteredВҰ104655 at the islandВҰ104658. It was decorated with carvings of the twin вҖҳgodsвҖҷ.
\v 12 We stayed threeВҰ104669 daysВҰ104667 when weВҰ104666 arrived at SyracuseВҰ104665
\v 13 andВҰ104677 thenВҰ104677 we sailed on to RhegiumВҰ104676. The next day a southВҰ104682 wind came so we sailed on to PuteoliВҰ104686
\v 14 whereВҰ104687 we foundВҰ104688 some believersВҰ104689 andВҰ104698 they encouraged us to stay for sevenВҰ104697 daysВҰ104696. ThenВҰ104698 we \add finally\add* got to RomeВҰ104703.
\v 15 The believersВҰ104707 in Rome had heardВҰ104708 about us, so they cameВҰ104712 to meet us at the AppiusВҰ104720 MarketВҰ104721 and the ThreeВҰ104723 TavernsВҰ104724. PaulВҰ104728 was encouraged to see them and thankedВҰ104729 \nd GodВҰ104731\nd*.
\s1 Paul preaches in Rome
\rem /s1 In Rome
\p
\v 16 WhenВҰ104735 weВҰ104736 got into RomeВҰ104740 proper, PaulВҰ104751 was allowed to live by himselfВҰ104756, with just a soldierВҰ104761 guardingВҰ104759 himВҰ104760.
\rem /s1 Paul Preaches at Rome under Guard; Paul and Jewish Leaders in Rome
\p
\v 17 After threeВҰ104766 daysВҰ104765, he called together the leadersВҰ104775 of the Jews \add in Rome\add*, and when they'd all gathered he spoke to them, вҖңMen, brothersВҰ104786, I have done nothingВҰ104788 against my peopleВҰ104792 or against our ancestralВҰ104797 customsВҰ104795. I was taken prisonerВҰ104798 in Yerushalem and handed over to the Romans
\v 18 who, after examiningВҰ104808 me, wanted to release me becauseВҰ104814 I had done nothing worthy of execution.
\v 19 But in defending myself against the Jews there, I felt compelledВҰ104826 to appealВҰ104827 to CaesarВҰ104828, although I myself had no complaint against the Jews.
\v 20 SoВҰ104841 that was why I called for you and wanted to addressВҰ104849 you, becauseВҰ104851 I am in chainsВҰ104857 for the sake of Yisrael's hopeвҖ”\add the messiah\add*.вҖқ
\p
\v 21 вҖңWe haven't receivedВҰ104872 any correspondence here about you,вҖқ they answered. вҖңNor have any of our brothersВҰ104880 \add from Yerushalem\add* arrivedВҰ104877 here to reportВҰ104881 any crimes of yours.
\v 22 But we would very much like to hearВҰ104893 from you about your thinkingВҰ104895, because we've certainly heard about this new sect because everyoneВҰ104907 is speaking out againstВҰ104908 it.вҖқ
\rem /s1 Paul Preaches in Rome
\p
\v 23 ThenВҰ104910 they set a dayВҰ104912 when they could visit him where he was staying and so that from morningВҰ104948 to eveningВҰ104950 he could explainВҰ104922 about God's kingdomВҰ104928 and show them how Mosheh's law and the prophets' writings spoke about \nd Yeshua\nd*.
\v 24 Afterwards some were persuadedВҰ104955 while othersВҰ104959 didn't find it believable.
\v 25 They argued back and forth, and as theyВҰ104967 were about to leave, PaulВҰ104970 shared this finalВҰ104972 messageВҰ104971, вҖңThe holy \nd spiritВҰ104976\nd* spokeВҰ104979 rightly through Yeshayah the prophetВҰ104984 to yourВҰ104988 ancestorsВҰ104987, saying:
\q1
\v 26 Go to these peopleВҰ104999 and tell them,
\q1 When you listen you will hearВҰ105003 but not understandВҰ105009,
\q1 and when you look you will see but not perceiveВҰ105017 it.
\q1
\v 27 BecauseВҰ105020 these people'sВҰ105024 minds have becomeВҰ105019 dull
\q2 and they can barely hear with their ears
\q2 and they shut their eyes,
\q1 just in case their eyes might actually see,
\q2 and their ears might actually hear,
\q2 and they might understandВҰ105048 with their minds,
\q1 and turn back to me
\q2 and then I would heal them.
\p
\v 28 SoВҰ105057 now let itВҰ105058 be knownВҰ105056 to youВҰ105059 all that the \add message of\add* salvationВҰ105067 from \nd GodВҰ105069\nd* has been sentВҰ105064 out to non-Jews andВҰ105071 theyВҰ105070 will listen.вҖқ
\p
\v 29 в—ҳ
\v 30 Paul remainedВҰ105085 in his own rentalВҰ105095 accommodation in Rome for twoВҰ105091 wholeВҰ105092 yearsВҰ105091 andВҰ105096 welcomedВҰ105097 everyone who went to see himВҰ105102,
\v 31 telling them about God's kingdomВҰ105105 andВҰ105108 boldly teachingВҰ105109 about the \nd masterВҰ105113 Yeshua\nd* without any hindrance.
